{"title_page": "Philip of Ibelin (died 1318)", "text_new": "{{more footnotes|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Expand German|Philipp von Ibelin (Seneschall von Zypern)|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Armoiries Ibelin.svg|thumb|right|150px|Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.]]\n\n'''Philip of Ibelin''' (born c. 1255; died 25 November 1318, [[Nicosia]]) was [[Seneschal]] of the [[Kingdom of Cyprus]]. As one of the sons of Philippa Barlais and her husband [[Guy of Ibelin, constable of Cyprus|Guy of Ibelin]], he was a member of the [[house of Ibelin]].\n\nHe married to: 1. c. 1280 Maria, daughter of Vahran of Hamousse by Mary of Ibelin, without issue; 2. c. 1295 Maria [[Embriaco]] of Gibelletto (d. 1331) with whom he had a son:\n* [[Guy of Ibelin, seneschal of Cyprus]]. He married to Margaret of Ibelin. Issue:\n** John of Ibelin (d. after 1367), seneschal of Cyprus after his father's death.\n** [[Alice of Ibelin]] (d. after 1374), who married John of Lusignan (1329/30-1375), titular Prince of Antioch and Regent of Cyprus.\n** Margaret of Ibelin.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* [[Templar of Tyre]], ''[[Gestes des Chiprois]] III,'' edited in: ''[[Recueil des historiens des croisades]], Documents arm\u00e9niens.'' Bd. 2 (1906), S. 737\u2013872.\n* Ren\u00e9 de Mas Latrie (ed.), ''Chroniques d\u2019Amadi et de Strambaldi,'' Bd. 1. Paris 1891.\n\n[[category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[category:13th-century births]]\n[[category:1318 deaths]]\n[[category:People of the Kingdom of Cyprus]]\n\n{{Cyprus-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{more footnotes|date=December 2016}}\n\n{{Expand German|Philipp von Ibelin (Seneschall von Zypern)|date=December 2016}}\n[[File:Armoiries Ibelin.svg|thumb|right|150px|Coat-of-arms of Ibelin.]]\n\n'''Philip of Ibelin''' (born c. 1255; died 25 November 1318, [[Nicosia]]) was [[Seneschal]] of the [[Kingdom of Cyprus]]. As one of the sons of Philippa Barlais and her husband [[Guy of Ibelin, constable of Cyprus|Guy of Ibelin]], he was a member of the [[house of Ibelin]].\n\nHe married to: 1. c. 1280 Maria, daughter of Vahran of Hamousse by Mary of Ibelin, without issue; 2. c. 1295 Maria [[Embriaco]] of Gibelletto (d. 1331) with whom he had a son:\n* [[Guy of Ibelin, seneschal of Cyprus]]. He married to Margaret of Ibelin. Issue:\n** John of Ibelin (d. after 1367), seneschal of Cyprus after his father's death.\n** Alice of Ibelin (d. after 1374), who married John of Lusignan (1329/30-1375), titular Prince of Antioch and Regent of Cyprus.\n** Margaret of Ibelin.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n\n* [[Templar of Tyre]], ''[[Gestes des Chiprois]] III,'' edited in: ''[[Recueil des historiens des croisades]], Documents arm\u00e9niens.'' Bd. 2 (1906), S. 737\u2013872.\n* Ren\u00e9 de Mas Latrie (ed.), ''Chroniques d\u2019Amadi et de Strambaldi,'' Bd. 1. Paris 1891.\n\n[[category:House of Ibelin]]\n[[category:13th-century births]]\n[[category:1318 deaths]]\n[[category:People of the Kingdom of Cyprus]]\n\n{{Cyprus-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "ArisMethymna", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Philip_of_Ibelin_(died_1318)"}
{"title_page": "The Big Day (album)", "text_new": "{{Infobox album\n| name         = The Big Day\n| type         = studio\n| artist       = [[Chance the Rapper]]\n| cover        = Chance the Rapper - The Big Day.png\n| alt          = A photograph of a hand holding up a transparent CD covered with diamonds\n| released     = {{start date|2019|07|26|mf=y}}\n| recorded     = <!-- Please source recording dates/years -->\n| studio       = \n| genre        = {{hlist|[[Pop-rap]]|[[gospel rap]]|[[contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[soul music|soul]]}}\n| length       = <!-- Duration template not needed per [[Template:Infobox album#length]] -->77:23\n| label        = <!-- Chance is not signed, and is selling the album (in part) through his own website. Take any objections to the talk page. -->[[Self-publishing|Self-released]]\n| producer     = {{hlist|[[Chance the Rapper]] <!-- Do not make text in infoboxes small per [[MOS:SMALLTEXT]] -->(also {{abbr|exec.|executive producer}})|[[Thirdstory|Ben Lusher]]|Carter Lang|Charlie Handsome|Darius Scott|DeMartis 'Sax' Williams|Dex Coleman|Dwayne Verner Jr.|Eric Butler|[[Francis Farewell Starlite|Francis Starlite]]|Gabe Jaskowiak|Garren Langford|Greg Landfair|Jordan Ware|[[Justin Vernon]]|[[Lido (musician)|Lido]]|[[Murda Beatz]]|Nate Fox|[[Nico Segal]]|Peter Cottontale|[[Pi'erre Bourne]]|Smoko Ono|[[Timbaland]]|TrapMoneyBenny}}\n| prev_title   = [[Merry Christmas Lil' Mama|Merry Christmas Lil' Mama Re-Wrapped]]\n| prev_year    = 2017\n| next_title   = \n| next_year    = \n| misc         = {{Singles\n| single1      = Do You Remember\n| single1date  = August 16, 2019<ref>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190819175948/https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3tqPdBWF9yMbTrfjWvfKV8t/radio-1-playlist|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/articles/3tqPdBWF9yMbTrfjWvfKV8t/radio-1-playlist|title=Radio 1 Playlist|publisher=[[BBC Radio 1]]|archivedate=August 19, 2019|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n| single2      = Hot Shower\n| single2date  = September 25, 2019\n}}\n}}\n'''''The Big Day''''' is the debut studio album by American rapper [[Chance the Rapper]], released on July 26, 2019.<ref name=\"Billboard\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8520285/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day|title=Chance The Rapper Announces Debut Album 'The Big Day,' Release Date and Cover Art|work=[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]|last=Brandle|first=Lars|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref> The album follows several mixtapes by the rapper including the reissue of his collaborative ''[[Merry Christmas Lil' Mama]]'' in 2017, and is his first solo project since ''[[Coloring Book (mixtape)|Coloring Book]]'' in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/chance-the-rapper-reveals-new-album-title-artwork-release-date/|title=Chance the Rapper Reveals New Album Title, Artwork, Release Date|website=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Minsker|first=Evan|date=July 17, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref> The album was influenced by Chance's marriage, which occurred in March 2019.<ref name=\"P4k\" /> The album was met with positive, albeit lukewarm, reviews from critics, but received backlash from fans on social media.<ref name=\"MC\" /><ref name=\"Crit1\"/><ref name=\"Crit2\"/> The album debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]], Chance's highest-charting entry to date.<ref name=\"BB200\" />\n\n== Recording ==\nIn a November 2016 interview, Chance the Rapper stated: \"I think what I'm working on now is an album.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.xxlmag.com/news/2016/11/chance-the-rapper-official-debut-album/|title=Chance The Rapper Is Officially Working on His Debut Album|work=[[XXL (magazine)|XXL]]|last=Weinstein|first=Max|date=November 23, 2016|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref> In May and June 2018, American rapper and producer [[Kanye West]] released a set of 7-track albums as part of the [[Wyoming Sessions]], producing five albums in collaboration with [[Pusha T]], [[Kid Cudi]], [[Nas]], and [[Teyana Taylor]]. In July 2018, Chance announced that West was coming to Chicago to produce his debut album.<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/hip-hop/8465190/chance-the-rapper-kanye-west-chicago-produce-new-album|title=Chance the Rapper Says Kanye West Is Heading to Chicago to Produce His New Album|magazine=Billboard|date=July 12, 2018|author=Carl Lamarre|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref> West arrived in Chicago in mid-August 2018 and began recording.<ref name=\"August\">{{Cite news|url=https://chicago.suntimes.com/entertainment/kanye-west-chicago-chance-the-rapper-album/|title=Kanye West in Chicago working with Chance the Rapper|date=August 29, 2018|accessdate=27 July 2019|publisher=Chicago Sun-Time|author=Alice Bazerghi}}</ref> The duo later announced that their collaboration would be titled ''Good Ass Job''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://genius.com/a/chance-the-rapper-kanye-west-tease-new-album-good-ass-job-update|title=Chance The Rapper & Kanye West Tease New Album \u2018Good Ass Job\u2019 (UPDATE)|website=Genius}}</ref> At the same time, West began working on his ninth studio album ''[[Yandhi]]'' and shifted his focus to that project instead; West has no production credits on the released version of ''The Big Day''.\n\n== Music and lyrics ==\n''The Big Day'' has been described by music journalists as a [[pop-rap]]<ref name=TheGuardian/> and [[gospel rap]] record.<ref>{{cite web|last=Heilman|first=Max|date=July 29, 2019|url=https://riffmagazine.com/album-reviews/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day/|title=REVIEW: Chance the Rapper\u2019s \u2018Big Day\u2019 becomes a jubilant gospel-rap excursion|website=Riff Magazine|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref> ''[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]]''{{'}}s Richard Trapunski says it \"presents a bigger and slicker version of [Chance the Rapper's] nostalgic gospel-rap sound\",<ref>{{cite news|last=Trapunski|first=Richard|date=July 29, 2019|url=https://nowtoronto.com/music/album-reviews/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day/|title=Review: The Big Day is Chance the Rapper's debut, but it suffers from the sophomore slump|newspaper=[[Now (newspaper)|NOW Magazine]]|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref> while Stephen Porzio from ''[[Hot Press]]'' says it not only features [[hip hop music|hip hop]] but also [[contemporary R&B|R&B]] and [[soul music]].<ref name=\"HP\">{{cite magazine|last=Porzio|first=Stephen|date=August 21, 2019|url=https://www.hotpress.com/music/album-review-chance-rapper-big-day-22785794|title=Album Review: Chance The Rapper, The Big Day|magazine=[[Hot Press]]|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLyrically, the album follows Chance on his wedding day, inspired by his real-life marriage to Kirsten Corley in March 2019.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/people/2019/03/11/chance-rapper-marry-kirsten-corley-wedding/3128352002/|title=Chance The Rapper married longtime love Kirsten Corley over the weekend|publisher=[[USA Today]]|date=11 March 2019|accessdate=27 July 2019}}</ref> Its predominant theme of family is explored with most songs about Kirsten and Chance's family and children. The album features contributions from his brother [[Taylor Bennett (rapper)|Taylor Bennett]], who raps on \"Roo\", and his father Ken Bennett, who helped co-write \"Eternal\". In the skits \"Photo Ops\" and \"4 Quarters in the Black\", comedians [[John Witherspoon (actor)|John Witherspoon]] and [[Keith David]] play wise uncle characters to highlight the multigenerational aspect of weddings.<ref name=\"P4k\"/>\n\n== Artwork ==\nThe artwork for the album cover features a jewel encrusted clear disc, reminiscent of a wedding ring, referencing the album's wedding theme, and was created by artist [[Sara Shakeel]]. Chance the Rapper reached out to Shakeel via Instagram to commission a physical object in her unique Swarovski crystal-clad style to be photographed and used for the cover art. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.iowastatedaily.com/limelight/chance-the-rapper-new-album-the-big-day/article_def98378-a8bf-11e9-892c-b3161d68e91d.html|title=Chance the Rapper reveals details about new album|last=Owens|first=Tanner|date=|website=Iowa State Daily|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref> Shakeel also created artworks for the rapper's installation \"The Big Store\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://hypebeast.com/2019/7/chance-the-rapper-big-day-store-art-exhibition-pop-up-shop-sara-shakeel|title=Chance the Rapper Relaunches \"The Big Store\" Pop-Up Exhibition|website=HYPEBEAST|access-date=2019-11-29}}</ref>{{clear}}\n\n== Marketing and sales ==\nIn March 2017, Chance stated that he would sell his debut album, as opposed to the free release of his previous mixtapes.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/71587-chance-the-rapper-i-might-actually-sell-this-album/|title=Chance the Rapper: 'I Might Actually Sell This Album'|website=Pitchfork|last=Strauss|first=Matthew|date=March 13, 2017|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref> On February 12, 2019, Chance [[Twitter|tweeted]] \"July\" and shared a video on his Instagram revealing that he had \"been making music\" that fans could expect to arrive the same month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/chance-the-rapper-teases-new-album/|title=Chance the Rapper Says New Album Is Coming in July|website=Pitchfork|last=Blais-Billie|first=Braudie|date=February 12, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref> On June 27, Chance released a promotional video titled \"The Next Chapter Begins\", where a [[pre-order]] for the album was launched. His first two mixtapes, ''[[10 Day]]'' and ''[[Acid Rap]]'', were also put up on music [[Streaming media|streaming services]], and sold on vinyl alongside his third mixtape ''[[Coloring Book (mixtape)|Coloring Book]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/news/chance-the-rapper-mixtapes-acid-rap-and-10day-hit-streaming-listen/|title=Chance the Rapper's Mixtapes Are Now Streaming, Coming to Vinyl|website=Pitchfork|last=Bloom|first=Madison|date=June 28, 2019|accessdate=July 17, 2019}}</ref> On July 16, Chance the Rapper announced the album's title, release date and revealed its cover during his interview on ''[[The Tonight Show Starring Jimmy Fallon]]''.<ref name=\"Billboard\"/>\n\nOn August 4, 2019, ''The Big Day'' debuted at number two on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] with 108,000 [[album-equivalent unit]]s, of which 27,000 were pure album sales in its first week. It was Chance's highest-charting entry and his third release to hit the top 10 of the chart.<ref name=\"BB200\">{{cite web|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/chart-beat/8526019/nf-scores-second-no-1-album-billboard-200|title=NF Scores Second No. 1 Album on Billboard 200 Chart With 'The Search'|work=Billboard|last=Caulfield|first=Keith|date=August 4, 2019|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Critical reception==\n{{Album ratings\n| ADM = 6.8/10<ref name=\"ADM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.anydecentmusic.com/review/10002/Chance-The-Rapper-The-Big-Day.aspx|title=The Big Day by Chance The Rapper reviews|publisher=[[AnyDecentMusic?]]|accessdate=August 28, 2019}}</ref>\n| MC = 71/100<ref name=\"MC\">{{cite web|url=https://www.metacritic.com/music/the-big-day/chance-the-rapper|title=The Big Day by Chance the Rapper Reviews and Tracks|publisher=[[Metacritic]]|accessdate=August 1, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=\"AllMusic\">{{cite web|url=https://www.allmusic.com/album/the-big-day-mw0003301150|title=The Big Day \u2013 Chance the Rapper|publisher=[[AllMusic]]|last=Thomas|first=Fred|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev2 = ''[[The A.V. Club]]''\n| rev2score = A<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.avclub.com/chance-the-rapper-celebrates-union-on-his-triumphant-st-1836787557|title=Chance The Rapper celebrates union on his triumphant studio release The Big Day|work=[[The A.V. Club]]|last=Itkoff|first=Adam Isaac|date=July 29, 2019|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev3 = ''[[Chicago Tribune]]''\n| rev3score = {{rating|3|4}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.chicagotribune.com/entertainment/music/greg-kot/ct-ent-chance-the-rapper-the-big-day-review-0727-20190726-6vltncrstvhtxnvvxdr3buus5u-story.html|title=Review: Chance the Rapper's new 'The Big Day'|work=[[Chicago Tribune]]|last=Kot|first=Greg|authorlink=Greg Kot|date=July 26, 2019|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev4 = ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]''\n| rev4score = A\u2212<ref name=\"EW\">{{cite web|url=https://ew.com/music/2019/07/29/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day-ew-review/|title=The Big Day is Chance the Rapper's ode to marital bliss|work=[[Entertainment Weekly]]|last=Weingarten|first=Christopher R.|date=July 29, 2019|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev5 = ''[[The Guardian]]''\n| rev5score = {{rating|4|5}}<ref name=TheGuardian>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/music/2019/jul/29/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day-review|title=Chance the Rapper: The Big Day review \u2013 a pop-rap marriage made in heaven|work=[[The Guardian]]|last=Horner|first=Al|date=July 29, 2019|accessdate=July 29, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev6 = ''[[Hot Press]]''\n| rev6Score = 7/10<ref name=\"HP\"/>\n| rev7 = ''[[The Independent]]''\n| rev7score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/reviews/chance-the-rapper-review-the-big-day-album-features-tracklist-berlin-transcendance-a9029576.html|title=Album reviews: Chance the Rapper \u2013 The Big Day, and Berlin \u2013 Transcendance|work=[[The Independent]]|last1=O'Connor|first1=Roisin|last2=Bray|first2=Elisa|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref> \n| rev8 = ''[[NME]]''\n| rev8score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"NME\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/reviews/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day-review-2533182|title=Chance The Rapper \u2013 \u2018The Big Day\u2019 review|work=[[NME]]|date=July 29, 2019|accessdate=November 28, 2019|last=Balram|first=Dhruva}}</ref>\n| rev9 = ''[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]''\n| rev9score = 6.9/10<ref>{{cite web|url=https://pitchfork.com/reviews/albums/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day/|title=Chance the Rapper: The Big Day|work=[[Pitchfork (website)|Pitchfork]]|last=Pearce|first=Sheldon|date=July 30, 2019|accessdate=July 30, 2019}}</ref>\n| rev10 = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev10score = {{rating|3|5}}<ref name=\"RS\">{{cite web|url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/music-album-reviews/chance-the-rapper-the-big-day-865145/|title=Chance the Rapper's 'The Big Day' is the Sound of a Man in Love and Sometimes That's Awesome|work=[[Rolling Stone]]|last=Schwartz|first=Danny|date=July 31, 2019|accessdate=July 31, 2019}}</ref>\n}}\n''The Big Day'' was met with generally positive reviews, according to the aggregate website [[Metacritic]]. At the website, which assigns a normalized rating out of 100 to reviews from professional critics, the album received an [[Weighted arithmetic mean|average score]] of 71, based on 21 reviews.<ref name=\"MC\"/> Aggregator [[AnyDecentMusic?]] gave it 6.8 out of 10, based on their assessment of the critical consensus.<ref name=\"ADM\"/> The reception was described as \"lukewarm\" by journalists Shaad D'Souza of ''[[The Fader]]''<ref>{{cite web|last=D'Souza|first=Shaad|date=August 2, 2019|url=https://www.thefader.com/2019/08/02/chance-the-rapper-zane-lowe-2019-transcript-watch-kanye-2019|title=5 takeaways from Chance The Rapper\u2019s Zane Lowe interview|website=[[The Fader]]|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref> and [[Gothamist]]'s Ben Yakas.<ref>{{cite web|last=Yakas|first=Ben|date=October 28, 2019|url=https://gothamist.com/arts-entertainment/videos-chance-rapper-carries-solid-snl-his-shoulders|title=Videos: Chance The Rapper Carries A Solid SNL On His Shoulders|website=[[Gothamist]]|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nReviewing in July 2019, Al Horner of ''[[The Guardian]]'' described ''The Big Day'' as \"a candid, cutesy [[concept album]] based around his wedding\", believing it \"combines something old and something new, subtly expanding Chance\u2019s sound without ever straying too far from the sentimental gospel-pop heart of his last release, ''[[Coloring Book (mixtape)|Coloring Book]]''.\"<ref name=TheGuardian/> Fred Thomas of [[AllMusic]] wrote that \"Bright, flawless production supports Chance's optimistic lyrics and cultivates an atmosphere overflowing with joy, wonder, and summery nostalgia.\"<ref name=\"AllMusic\"/> Christopher Weingarten of ''[[Entertainment Weekly]]'' concluded: \"A master lyricist, a musical omnivore, Chance and his family of producers and instrumentalists channel all the big emotions of the big day in a swirl of bliss, marital and otherwise.\"<ref name=\"EW\"/> In a less enthusiastic review, Danny Schwartz of ''[[Rolling Stone]]'' concluded that, \"Despite its length, ''The Big Day'' is self-contained, at least by Chance\u2019s standards\", considering it \"narrower in emotional scope\" than the 2016 mixtape ''Coloring Book''.<ref name=\"RS\"/> Dhruva Balram of ''[[NME]]'' said it is \"a buoyant, cheerful project that looks back on his young, successful career through rose-tinted lenses but, ultimately, doesn't possess enough depth amidst a mishmash of production and features that make it too long-winded.\"<ref name=\"NME\"/> \n\nThe album and Chance received criticism from fans on social media, spawning many [[Internet meme]]s primarily about the album's focus on Chance's marriage. Some fans also had expected content reminiscent of his earlier releases and believed that the album did not meet up to said expectations, it being considered by most to be a major drop in quality for the artist. Music critic [[Anthony Fantano]] of ''The Needle Drop'' gave the album a rare zero rating out of ten and listed the album as the second worst album of 2019.<!-- Do NOT remove; per [[WP:NOTRSMUSIC]], \"Fantano is usable if his review was published by a third party\"--><ref name=\"TND\">{{Cite web|url=https://junkee.com/chance-rapper-memes/216547|title=The Internet Is Awash With Memes About Chance The Rapper Loving His Wife|website=[[Junkee]]|last=Earp|first=Joseph|date=August 2, 2019|accessdate=August 9, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://dontboreus.thebrag.com/chance-the-rapper-loves-his-wife-memes-are-rolling-in/|title=Chance the Rapper loves his wife, and the memes are rolling in|website=[[The Brag Media#Don't Bore Us|Don't Bore Us]]|last=Di Iorio|first=Michael|date=August 3, 2019|accessdate=August 11, 2019}}</ref> Chance responded on Twitter to the criticism that he believes that people want him to \"kill himself\".<ref name=\"Crit1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.nme.com/news/music/im-getting-this-crazy-feeling-that-people-want-me-to-kill-myself-chance-the-rapper-on-the-big-day-fan-backlash-2535368|title=\"I'm getting this crazy feeling that people want me to kill myself\" \u2013 Chance The Rapper on 'The Big Day' fan backlash|work=NME|last=Lavin|first=Will|date=August 5, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"Crit2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/music/news/chance-the-rapper-new-album-big-day-review-reaction-twitter-songs-track-list-a9040251.html|title=Chance the Rapper posts lengthy and emotional response to new album criticism|work=[[The Independent]]|last=Harrison|first=Ellie|date=August 5, 2019|accessdate=August 7, 2019}}</ref>\n\nVeteran music critic [[Robert Christgau]] believed ''The Big Day'' had become a \"backlash victim\", instead ranking it on his year-end list as 2019's third best album.<ref name=\"xgau2019\">{{cite web|last=Christgau|first=Robert|date=January 26, 2020|url=https://robertchristgau.substack.com/p/deans-list-2019|title=Dean's List 2019|work=And It Don't Stop|publisher=Substack|accessdate=January 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\nTrack listing and credits adapted from [[Apple Music]] and [[Tidal (service)|Tidal]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://music.apple.com/us/album/the-big-day/1474378343|title=The Big 