{"title_page": "Hong Kong Canadians", "text_new": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group      = Hong Kong Canadians\n| population = '''616,000'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121017233944/http://www.ocac.gov.tw/stat/chinese/global/canada/ca_pop_hk-sex%26age%26gen-01.pdf]</ref><br>\n205,430 (born in Hong Kong)<ref name=nhs2011>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |title=NHS Profile, Canada, 2011;}}</ref>\n| region1    = {{flag|Ontario}}\n| pop1       = [[Toronto]]\n| ref1       = \n| region2    = {{flag|British Columbia}}\n| pop2       = [[Vancouver]]\n| ref2       = \n| region3    = {{flag|Alberta}}\n| pop3       = [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]]\n| ref3       =\n|langs       = [[English language|English]], [[Cantonese]]\n|rels        = [[Anglicanism]], [[Catholicism]], [[Protestantism]], [[Mahayana]] Buddhism, [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]]\n|related     = [[Chinese Canadians]], [[Taiwanese Canadians]] \n}}\n\n'''Hong Kong Canadians''' or '''Canadians of Hong Kong resident''' ({{zh|\u9999\u6e2f\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u4eba}} or {{lang|zh|\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u6e2f\u4eba}}), include Hong Kong permanent residents who identify themselves as Hongkongers(who see Hong Kong as their home and are culturally associated with Hong Kong, especially through descent, growth, birth, long term residence in Hong Kong, or other types of deep affiliations with Hong Kong), Canadians who were born by [[Hongkongers|Hong Kongers]] as well as Canadians of [[Hongkongers|Hong Kong]] ancestry (Chinese). \n\nThe largest wave of immigration to Canada from Hong Kong occurred during the late 1980s and early 1990s, due chiefly to the fear of uncertainties concerning the [[transfer of sovereignty of Hong Kong]] in 1997.\n\nThe {{cn-span|text=vast majority{{how|date=July 2017}} of Canadians of Hong Kong origin are ethnically [[Han Chinese|Chinese]] and Chinese nationality,|date=July 2017}} though some choose to eschew their \"Chinese\" identity due to racism against Chinese under British rule during colonization.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=Edward|last2=Wong|first2=Alan|title=Seeking Identity, \u2018Hong Kong People\u2019 Look to City, Not State|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/08/world/asia/hong-kong-people-looking-in-mirror-see-fading-chinese-identity.html?_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=Oct 7, 2014}}{{dubious|reason=Hong Kong is their city region which they identified with. |date=July 2017}}</ref> They often trace their ancestry to Chinese under different [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]], [[Hakka people|Hakka]], [[Hoklo people|Hoklo]] and [[Taishanese|Toisan]] cultural groups.\n\nMany{{how|date=July 2017}}{{weasel-inline|date=July 2017}} Hong Kong Canadians hold [[multiple citizenship]]s, often possessing Canadian and  Chinese HKSAR passports. Some{{howmany|date=July 2017}} Hong Kong Canadians have returned to Hong Kong from Canada since 1997 and have resettled in the HongKong permanently. As of 2014, Hong Kong has the highest concentration of Canadian citizens in Asia, with approximately 300,000 Canadian citizens of all ethnic backgrounds living in the city.<ref name=star>{{cite news|last1=Keung|first1=Nicholas|title=Hong Kong: Asia's most Canadian city|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2011/02/24/hong_kong_asias_most_canadian_city.html|newspaper=The Toronto Star|date=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, the majority of Hong Kong Canadians reside in the metropolitan areas of Toronto and Vancouver. Most of Hong Kong Canadians were born in Hong Kong, Canada or Guangdong, China. \n\n==History==\nThe majority{{howmany|date=July 2017}} of Chinese Canadians migrated to Canada from the mid 1980s to 2000. However early settlement could be traced back to the early 19th Century when [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] became a British [[crown colony]], natives from Kwangtung (now Guangdong) escaped and settled in Hong Kong for a short while before migrating to North America.\n\nIn 1984, the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] was signed which largely shaped the future politics and economy of Hong Kong. The then British colony would become a [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]]. Many people in Hong Kong at the time perceived a negative image of the China's government which was largely influenced by their experience with the illegal immigrants from the Canton province who smuggled into Hong Kong in the hope of finding freedom and better living standard than the lives ruled by the [[Chinese Communists]] {{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}.\n\nThe fear of losing their freedom and prosperity under the Chinese government drove some Hong Kong citizens to reject their Chinese identity. Their fear and worries were proved to be correct by the [[1989 Tiananmen Square Crackdown]] which later drove a large emigration wave to the anglophone world between 1980s to early 2000s. One of the most popular destination chosen by the immigrants was Canada, where thousands of Hongkongers settled in [[Greater Toronto]] and [[Metro Vancouver]].\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2006, among the 790,035 speakers of any of the [[varieties of Chinese]], 300,590 were speakers of [[Cantonese]].<ref>The 790,035 figure includes 300,590 persons listed as speaking Cantonese, 143,385 listed as speaking Mandarin, 4,580 listed as speaking Taiwanese, and 341,480 speaking other varieties or else simply filling out the relevant question on their census forms by noting \"Chinese\" without being more specific. See Statistics Canada, ''2006 Census Profile of Federal Electoral Districts (2003 Representation Order): Language, Mobility and Migration and Immigration and Citizenship.'' Ottawa, 2007, p. 8 and note no. 1 on p. 503.</ref> According to 2001 statistics, 44% of the Cantonese speakers were born in Hong Kong, 27% were born in Guangdong, the Chinese province where most{{howmany|date=July 2017}} Hongkongers have their ancestral roots, and 18% were Canadian-born.<ref name=\"StatCan\">{{cite journal|last1=Chui|first1=Tina|last2=Tran|first2=Kelly|last3=Flanders|first3=John|format=PDF|url=http://www.statcan.ca/english/freepub/11-008-XIE/0040411-008-XIE.pdf|title=Chinese Canadians: Enriching the cultural mosaic|journal=Canadian Social Trends|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|date=Spring 2005|issue=76|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511230136/http://www.statcan.ca/english/freepub/11-008-XIE/0040411-008-XIE.pdf|archivedate=May 11, 2008}}</ref>Among the Cantonese speakers who were born in Guangdong, a large percentage are Hong Kong immigrants. \n\nDuring the 2000s, some Canadian citizens from Hong Kong and their descendants have returned to Hong Kong for job opportunities. There are estimated to be as many as 300,000 [[Canadians in Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinareviewnews.com/doc/1016/1/1/6/101611635.html?coluid=7&kindid=0&docid=101611635&mdate=0226122246|title=\u4e2d\u570b\u8a55\u8ad6\u65b0\u805e\uff1a\u9999\u6e2f\u4f4f\u4e8630\u842c\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u4eba\u3000\u6210\u52a0\u570b\u7b2c16\u5927\u57ce\u5e02|work=chinareviewnews.com}}</ref> Conversely, according to the Canadian Consulate General in Hong Kong, there are 500,000 people of Hong Kong descent in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/hong_kong/bilateral_relations_bilaterales/canada_hk.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=8&menu=L|title=Canada-Hong Kong Relations|work=canadainternational.gc.ca}}</ref> Hong Kong boasts one of the largest Canadian communities abroad (an estimated 295,000). This community, along with some 500,000 people of Hong Kong descent in Canada, plays a dynamic role in building vibrant bilateral relations between Canada and Hong Kong.\n\nCanada's presence in Hong Kong is also reflected by the presence of Hong Kong-Canadian associations, such as the Chinese Canadian Association, established in 1989 and the Canadian University Association, which now acts as an umbrella group for some twenty Canadian university alumni associations active in Hong Kong today.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Canada|Hong Kong}}\n* [[Canadians in Hong Kong]]\n* [[Consulate General of Canada in Hong Kong]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* \"[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/society/immigration/chinese-immigration-to-canada-a-tale-of-perseverance/the-hong-kong-influx.html The Hong Kong influx].\" ''[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]''. 1997. [https://web.archive.org/web/20041114061538/http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-69-1433-9250/life_society/chinese_immigration/ Description page] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6TdHbG9vk?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20041114061538/http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-69-1433-9250/life_society/chinese_immigration/ Archived]).\n\n{{Asian Canadians}}\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Hongkongers abroad}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration to Canada|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hong Kong descent|*]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada]]\n[[Category:Asian Canadian]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong emigrants to Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong diaspora|Canada]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox ethnic group\n| group      = Hong Kong Canadians\n| population = '''616,000'''<ref>[https://web.archive.org/web/20121017233944/http://www.ocac.gov.tw/stat/chinese/global/canada/ca_pop_hk-sex%26age%26gen-01.pdf]</ref><br>\n205,430 (born in Hong Kong)<ref name=nhs2011>{{cite web |url=http://www12.statcan.gc.ca/nhs-enm/2011/dp-pd/prof/details/page.cfm?Lang=E&Geo1=PR&Code1=01&Data=Count&SearchText=canada&SearchType=Begins&SearchPR=01&A1=All&B1=All&Custom=&TABID=1 |title=NHS Profile, Canada, 2011;}}</ref>\n| region1    = {{flag|Ontario}}\n| pop1       = [[Toronto]]\n| ref1       = \n| region2    = {{flag|British Columbia}}\n| pop2       = [[Vancouver]]\n| ref2       = \n| region3    = {{flag|Alberta}}\n| pop3       = [[Calgary]], [[Edmonton]]\n| ref3       =\n|langs       = [[English language|English]], [[Cantonese]]\n|rels        = [[Anglicanism]], [[Catholicism]], [[Protestantism]], [[Mahayana]] Buddhism, [[Confucianism]], [[Taoism]]\n|related     = [[Chinese Canadians]], [[Taiwanese Canadians]] \n}}\n\n'''Hong Kong Canadians''' or '''Canadians of Hong Kong resident''' ({{zh|\u9999\u6e2f\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u4eba}} or {{lang|zh|\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u6e2f\u4eba}}), include Hong Kong permanent residents who identify themselves as Hongkongers(who see Hong Kong as their home and are culturally associated with Hong Kong, especially through descent, growth, birth, long term residence in Hong Kong, or other types of deep affiliations with Hong Kong), Canadians who were born by [[Hongkongers|Hong Kongers]] as well as Canadians of [[Hongkongers|Hong Kong]] ancestry (Chinese). \n\nThe largest wave of immigration to Canada from Hong Kong occurred during the late 1980s and early 1990s, due chiefly to the fear of uncertainties concerning the [[transfer of sovereignty of Hong Kong]] in 1997.\n\nThe {{cn-span|text=vast majority{{how|date=July 2017}} of Canadians of Hong Kong origin are ethnically [[Han Chinese|Chinese]] and Chinese nationality,|date=July 2017}} though some choose to eschew their \"Chinese\" identity due to racism against Chinese under British rule during colonization.<ref name=nytimes>{{cite news|last1=Wong|first1=Edward|last2=Wong|first2=Alan|title=Seeking Identity, \u2018Hong Kong People\u2019 Look to City, Not State|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2014/10/08/world/asia/hong-kong-people-looking-in-mirror-see-fading-chinese-identity.html?_r=0|newspaper=The New York Times|date=Oct 7, 2014}}{{dubious|reason=Hong Kong is their city region which they identified with. |date=July 2017}}</ref> They often trace their ancestry to Chinese under different [[Cantonese people|Cantonese]], [[Hakka people|Hakka]], [[Hoklo people|Hoklo]] and [[Taishanese|Toisan]] cultural groups.\n\nMany{{how|date=July 2017}}{{weasel-inline|date=July 2017}} Hong Kong Canadians hold [[multiple citizenship]]s, often possessing Canadian and  Chinese HKSAR passports. Some{{howmany|date=July 2017}} Hong Kong Canadians have returned to Hong Kong from Canada since 1997 and have resettled in the HongKong permanently. As of 2014, Hong Kong has the highest concentration of Canadian citizens in Asia, with approximately 300,000 Canadian citizens of all ethnic backgrounds living in the city.<ref name=star>{{cite news|last1=Keung|first1=Nicholas|title=Hong Kong: Asia's most Canadian city|url=https://www.thestar.com/news/canada/2011/02/24/hong_kong_asias_most_canadian_city.html|newspaper=The Toronto Star|date=February 24, 2011}}</ref>\n\nIn Canada, the majority of Hong Kong Canadians reside in the metropolitan areas of Toronto and Vancouver. Most of Hong Kong Canadians were born in Hong Kong, Canada or Guangdong, China. \n\n==History==\nThe majority{{howmany|date=July 2017}} of Chinese Canadians migrated to Canada from the mid 1980s to 2000. However early settlement could be traced back to the early 19th Century when [[British Hong Kong|Hong Kong]] became a British [[crown colony]], natives from Kwangtung (now Guangdong) escaped and settled in Hong Kong for a short while before migrating to North America.\n\nIn 1984, the [[Sino-British Joint Declaration]] was signed which largely shaped the future politics and economy of Hong Kong. The then British colony would become a [[Special Administrative Region of the People's Republic of China]]. Many people in Hong Kong at the time perceived a negative image of the China's government which was largely influenced by their experience with the illegal immigrants from the Canton province who smuggled into Hong Kong in the hope of finding freedom and better living standard than the lives ruled by the [[Chinese Communists]] {{Citation needed|date=November 2018}}.\n\nThe fear of losing their freedom and prosperity under the China's government drove some Hong Kong citizens to reject their Chinese identity. Their fear and worries were proved to be correct by the [[1989 Tiananmen Square Crackdown]] which later drove a large emigration wave to the anglophone world between 1980's to early 2000's. One of the most popular destination chosen by the immigrants was Canada, where thousands of Hongkongers settled in [[Greater Toronto]] and [[Metro Vancouver]].\n\n==Demographics==\nIn 2006, among the 790,035 speakers of any of the [[varieties of Chinese]], 300,590 were speakers of [[Cantonese]].<ref>The 790,035 figure includes 300,590 persons listed as speaking Cantonese, 143,385 listed as speaking Mandarin, 4,580 listed as speaking Taiwanese, and 341,480 speaking other varieties or else simply filling out the relevant question on their census forms by noting \"Chinese\" without being more specific. See Statistics Canada, ''2006 Census Profile of Federal Electoral Districts (2003 Representation Order): Language, Mobility and Migration and Immigration and Citizenship.'' Ottawa, 2007, p. 8 and note no. 1 on p. 503.</ref> According to 2001 statistics, 44% of the Cantonese speakers were born in Hong Kong, 27% were born in Guangdong, the Chinese province where most{{howmany|date=July 2017}} Hongkongers have their ancestral roots, and 18% were Canadian-born.<ref name=\"StatCan\">{{cite journal|last1=Chui|first1=Tina|last2=Tran|first2=Kelly|last3=Flanders|first3=John|format=PDF|url=http://www.statcan.ca/english/freepub/11-008-XIE/0040411-008-XIE.pdf|title=Chinese Canadians: Enriching the cultural mosaic|journal=Canadian Social Trends|publisher=[[Statistics Canada]]|date=Spring 2005|issue=76|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080511230136/http://www.statcan.ca/english/freepub/11-008-XIE/0040411-008-XIE.pdf|archivedate=May 11, 2008}}</ref>Among the Cantonese speakers who were born in Guangdong, a large percentage are Hong Kong immigrants. \n\nDuring the 2000s, some Canadian citizens from Hong Kong and their descendants have returned to Hong Kong for job opportunities. There are estimated to be as many as 300,000 [[Canadians in Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.chinareviewnews.com/doc/1016/1/1/6/101611635.html?coluid=7&kindid=0&docid=101611635&mdate=0226122246|title=\u4e2d\u570b\u8a55\u8ad6\u65b0\u805e\uff1a\u9999\u6e2f\u4f4f\u4e8630\u842c\u52a0\u62ff\u5927\u4eba\u3000\u6210\u52a0\u570b\u7b2c16\u5927\u57ce\u5e02|work=chinareviewnews.com}}</ref> Conversely, according to the Canadian Consulate General in Hong Kong, there are 500,000 people of Hong Kong descent in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.canadainternational.gc.ca/hong_kong/bilateral_relations_bilaterales/canada_hk.aspx?lang=eng&menu_id=8&menu=L|title=Canada-Hong Kong Relations|work=canadainternational.gc.ca}}</ref> Hong Kong boasts one of the largest Canadian communities abroad (an estimated 295,000). This community, along with some 500,000 people of Hong Kong descent in Canada, plays a dynamic role in building vibrant bilateral relations between Canada and Hong Kong.\n\nCanada's presence in Hong Kong is also reflected by the presence of Hong Kong-Canadian associations, such as the Chinese Canadian Association, established in 1989 and the Canadian University Association, which now acts as an umbrella group for some twenty Canadian university alumni associations active in Hong Kong today.\n\n== See also ==\n{{Portal|Canada|Hong Kong}}\n* [[Canadians in Hong Kong]]\n* [[Consulate General of Canada in Hong Kong]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== Further reading ==\n* \"[http://www.cbc.ca/archives/categories/society/immigration/chinese-immigration-to-canada-a-tale-of-perseverance/the-hong-kong-influx.html The Hong Kong influx].\" ''[[Canadian Broadcasting Corporation|CBC]]''. 1997. [https://web.archive.org/web/20041114061538/http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-69-1433-9250/life_society/chinese_immigration/ Description page] ([https://www.webcitation.org/6TdHbG9vk?url=http://web.archive.org/web/20041114061538/http://archives.cbc.ca/IDC-1-69-1433-9250/life_society/chinese_immigration/ Archived]).\n\n{{Asian Canadians}}\n{{People of Canada}}\n{{Hongkongers abroad}}\n\n[[Category:Immigration to Canada|*]]\n[[Category:Canadian people of Hong Kong descent|*]]\n[[Category:Ethnic groups in Canada]]\n[[Category:Asian Canadian]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong emigrants to Canada| ]]\n[[Category:Hong Kong diaspora|Canada]]\n", "name_user": "Alistair1978", "label": "safe", "comment": "typos (viaWP:JWB)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hong_Kong_Canadians"}
{"title_page": "Bristol Bay", "text_new": "[[File:Bristol Bay.png|thumb|upright=1.15|Map of Bristol Bay]]\n[[File:BristolBay2.jpg|thumb|[[Packraft]]s on Nushagak Bay]]\n[[File:Bristol Bay Fisherman.jpg|thumb|Bristol Bay fisherman]]\n'''Bristol Bay''' (''Iilgayaq'' in [[Yupik language|Central Yup'ik]], {{lang-ru|\u0417\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439}}<ref>[https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c8/Alaska_1844.jpg \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f \u0438 \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u043a\u0435\u0430\u043d\u0430 (1844)]</ref>) is the eastern-most arm of the [[Bering Sea]], at 57\u00b0 to 59\u00b0 North 157\u00b0 to 162\u00b0 West in [[Southwest Alaska]]. Bristol Bay is 400&nbsp;km (250&nbsp;mi) long and 290&nbsp;km, (180&nbsp;mi) wide at its mouth.  A number of rivers flow into the bay, including the [[Cinder River|Cinder]], [[Egegik River|Egegik]], [[Igushik River|Igushik]], [[Kvichak River|Kvichak]], [[Meshik River|Meshik]], [[Nushagak River|Nushagak]], [[Naknek River|Naknek]], [[Togiak River|Togiak]], and [[Ugashik River|Ugashik]].\n\nUpper reaches of Bristol Bay experience some of the highest tides in the world.  One such reach, the [[Nushagak Bay]] near [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]] and another near [[Naknek, Alaska|Naknek]] in [[Kvichak Bay]] have tidal extremes in excess of 10&nbsp;m (30&nbsp; ft), ranking them &mdash; and the area &mdash; as eighth highest in the world.  Coupled with the extreme number of shoals, sandbars, and shallows, makes navigation troublesome, especially during the area's frequently strong winds. As the shallowest part of the Bering Sea, Bristol Bay is one of the most dangerous regions for large vessels.\n\n<!--  These features are one reason why the Bristol Bay commercial salmon fishing fleet is limited to 32-foot (10 m) overall keel length.{{Fact|date=September 2008}} Also, most of the area is not well documented by nautical charts and navigational aids are sparse.{{Fact|date=September 2008}} I removed this section to the discussion page for further debate and to dispute this \"fact.\"  I'm from Bristol Bay, and there is no citation included in this \"fact,\" which I believe to be false.  ~~~~ -->\n\n== History ==\n[[File:BristolBay3.jpg|thumb|Tundra landscape near Bristol Bay]]\nIn ancient times, much of Bristol Bay was dry and arable, along with much of the [[Bering land bridge|Bering Sea Land Bridge]].  More recently, its proximity to mineral, animal and seafood riches provided an incentive for human habitation along its shoreline. Early Russian and English exploration provided most of the non-native influences of the area. During his voyage through the area in 1778, the famed British navigator and explorer, Captain [[James Cook]] named the area \"in honor of the [[Augustus Hervey, 3rd Earl of Bristol|Admiral Earl of Bristol]]\" in England.\n\n=== Early settlement ===\n[[File:BristolBay4.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Shore of Bristol Bay]]\nAfter establishing some temporary settlements in the late 1790s, The [[Russian American Company]] sent exploratory parties to document the coast and nearby inland areas of Bristol Bay. One of these charted the area between the [[Kuskokwim River|Kuskokwim]] and [[Nushagak River]]s. The original Eskimo village at Naknek went through various names as recorded by the Russians after they arrived in the area in 1819 (1821-\u201cNaugeik\u201d; 1880- \u201cKinuyak\u201d; and finally Naknek as named by Russian Navy Captain Tebenkov). Later, in 1819, an [[Aleut people|Aleut]] by the name of Andrei Ustiugov drew the first intensive charts of Bristol Bay.  Additionally, ships of the [[Russian Navy]] conducted extensive surveys of the Bering Sea coastline into the mid-19th century, naming many of the geographical features commonly used today: Capes Constantine, Chichagof, Menshikof and Greig, Mounts [[Veniaminof]] and [[Mount Pavlof|Pavlof]], [[Becharof Lake]], etc. In 1883 the first salmon cannery was open in Bristol Bay\u201d <ref>https://www.nps.gov/lacl/learn/historyculture/upload/Canneries-Cabins-Caches-508-compliant-Sept-2015-low-res.pdf</ref> (Source information from the cannery article to give context on the expansion of the salmon industry in Alaska and the history of growth.\n\nThe influence of the Katmai Volcano Explosion in 1912 and the influenza epidemic in 1919 decimated the Naknek people and area. According to oral history, there were only about three original families left at that time.<ref>(https://www.nps.gov/lacl/learn/historyculture/upload/Canneries-Cabins-Caches-508-compliant-Sept-2015-low-res.pdf)</ref>\n\n=== World War Two ===\nOn July 7,{{Clarify|reason=what year?|date=June 2019}} Alaskans witnessed conflict as Japanese fishing vessels entered the waters of Bristol Bay with 10,000-ton fishing trawlers to harvest salmon.\n\nAt that time, the Fisheries Bureau prohibited the use of motorized vessels, fish traps, and purse seines in Alaska. This was to ensure a 50% escapement of the spawning salmon, to guarantee their sustainability.\n\nThe Japanese fleet was composed of diesel-powered steel vessels. The Japanese had a technological advantage over the American fisherman and dominated the bay that summer.\n\nIn 1938, the United States agreed with Japan that the Japanese would refrain from fishing in Alaskan waters. This agreement was honored until Japan and the United States entered World War 2. In the 1950s, Japan was strengthening its fishing presence in the Pacific; the US, Canada, and Japan passed the North Pacific Fisheries Treaty. This treaty managed the resources of the region jointly to preserve the future generations of fish. This agreement is the model for international fisheries regulations today.<ref>http://www.visitbristolbay.com/visitor-guide/cultures.html</ref>\n\n== Industry ==\n[[File:BristolBay5.jpg|thumb|Nushagak River, draining into Bristol Bay]]\n\nBristol Bay is home to the world's most abundant [[sockeye salmon]] [[fishery]] as well as strong runs of chum salmon, silver salmon, and king salmon, each occurring seasonally.<ref>La Ganga, Maria L. (December 16, 2014) [http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-bristol-bay-leases-20141216-story.html \"Obama protects Alaska's Bristol Bay from oil and gas drilling\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref>  Kings are usually the first to run up the river followed by reds and chums.  Silvers and Pinks are the last to run up the river.\nOn an international scale, sockeye salmon are a relatively rare creature. Like other wild salmon species, sockeye harvests fluctuate but comprise 4 to 7 percent of global salmon production and 13 to 20 percent of native salmon harvests. Between 2011 and 2014, sockeye accounted for 5 percent of the world's salmon harvest by volume and 15 percent of the world's wild salmon harvest.\n\n===Commercial fishing===\nBristol Bay is home to the world's largest salmon run. All five Eastern Pacific species spawn in the bay's freshwater tributaries. Commercial fisheries include the world's largest sockeye salmon fishery.<ref>http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/index.cfm?adfg=commercialbyareabristolbay.main</ref> The Kvijack drains from Lake Iliamna, which is downstream of the deposit. Along with herring and other fisheries, salmon account for nearly 75% of local jobs.\n\nDuring the first 50 years of commercial salmon fishing in Bristol Bay, the fishing boats were restricted to sail power. When this restriction lifted in 1951, it took only seven short years to outfit all the boats (approximately 1,500) with diesel or gas engines. In the late 1920s another law was passed restricting the length of the boats to 32 feet. This law holds true even today.<ref>http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/index.cfm?adfg=commercialbyareabristolbay.main</ref>\n\n=== Canneries ===\nBristol Bay is a remote part of Alaska. The canneries preserve the freshness of the salmon which are gutted, cleaned, and processed on site. These companies have established a presence in Bristol Bay.\n\nCanneries include North Pacific Seafoods,Togiak Seafoods, Bristol Bay Setnet, Friedman Family Fisheries, Peter Pan Seafoods, Ekuk Fisheries, Big Creek Shore plant, Coffee Point Seafood, Icicle Seafoods, Wild Premium Salmon, Seafood Enterprises of Alaska, Alaska General Seafoods, Alaska Salmon Wild, Da Kine Enterprise, Extreme Salmon, Great Ruby Fish, My Girl, Naknek Family Fisheries, North Pacific Seafoods, Ocean Beauty, Silver Bay Seafoods, Trident Seafoods, Tulchina Fisheries, Diamond Lodge Smokehouse, and Nakeen Homepack.\n\n[[File:Bristol Bay shore.jpg|thumb|left|Shore of Bristol Bay near [[Naknek, Alaska|Naknek]]]]\nMajor industries are [[commercial fishing]] and the associated canneries, [[sport fishing]], [[hunting]] and [[tourism]].  The number of business lodges, hunting- and fishing-resorts and visitors to the nearby [[Katmai National Park and Preserve]] has grown exponentially in recent years. Sports fishing is another important local industry. Many lodges cater to sport fishermen targeting the salmon and trout populations in the freshwater tributaries. Freshwater species include humpback whitefish (Coregonus pidschianpp), Dolly Varden trout (Salvelinus malma), and Rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss).[18]\n\nThe area has also experienced significant interest in oil and mineral development, most notably with the proposed [[Pebble Mine]] on the north shore of [[Iliamna Lake]], and auctioning of leases to tracts in the southern Bristol Bay area known as the [[North Aleutians Basin]], an area which has been closed to offshore oil and gas development since a moratorium in 1998.  The draft plan by the [[Bureau of Land Management]] (pending public comments until 2/5/2007), also proposes to open most of the BLM's {{convert|3600000|acres}} in the area to [[Underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock mining]] and oil and gas drilling.\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:BristolBay1.jpg|thumb|upright|Abandoned cabin on Bristol Bay]]\nThe three largest communities of the Bristol Bay area are [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]], [[King Salmon, Alaska|King Salmon]], and [[Naknek, Alaska|Naknek]].  Smaller communities which dot the coastline and rivers of Bristol Bay include: [[Egegik, Alaska|Egegik]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u026a|\u0261|\u025b|\u0261|\u026a|k}}, [[Ekuk, Alaska|Ekuk]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|k|o\u028a|k}}, [[Igiugig, Alaska|Igiugig]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|d\u0292|i\u02d0|\u02c8|j|\u0254\u02d0|\u0261|\u026a|\u0261}},{{Dubious|date=May 2009}} [[Manokotak, Alaska|Manokotak]] {{IPAc-en|m|\u0251\u02d0|n|\u0259|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|t|\u0251\u02d0|k}}, [[New Stuyahok, Alaska|New Stuyahok]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|t|u\u02d0|j|\u0259|h|\u0252|k}}, [[Newhalen, Alaska|Newhalen]], [[Nondalton, Alaska|Nondalton]], [[Pilot Point, Alaska|Pilot Point]], [[Port Heiden, Alaska|Port Heiden]], [[Ugashik, Alaska|Ugashik]] ({{IPAc-en|j|u\u02d0|\u02c8|\u0261|\u00e6|\u0283|\u026a|k}}, and South Naknek.\n\nAll of these communities are primarily inhabited by [[Alaska Natives]], except for [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]] and [[King Salmon, Alaska|King Salmon]]; the former being influenced early-on by white salmon-cannery employees of European descent and the latter being heavily populated by military personnel stationed, primarily during Cold War years, at the nearby King Salmon Air Force Station and later by visitors and employees of the nearby [[Katmai National Park and Preserve]].\n\n== Proposed Pebble Mine ==\n{{Main|Pebble Mine}}\nA mineral exploration project investigating a large [[porphyry copper]], [[gold]], and [[molybdenum]] deposit in the Bristol Bay region has been proposed and may be undertaken by British-Australian<ref>http://www.riotinto.com/documents/140415_Rio_Tinto_delivers_strong_first_quarter_production.pdf</ref> [[Rio Tinto Group]] and Japanese <ref>https://www.nrdc.org/stories/crushing-alaskas-pebble-mine</ref> [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] [[Mitsubishi]]. Northern Dynasty Minerals LLC staked a claim on the site in 2001 and with its partners, invested 500 million dollars into the project. The mining company lost all of its partners in 2011 due to increasing government regulations and distrust by its partners.\n\nBecause of the estimated 10 billion tons of mining waste that must be permanently stored in the area, which is an active earthquake zone, and Rio Tinto's environmental track record, which is seen as poor by many environmental advocacy groups, fears have been raised about the potential impact on the Bristol Bay area and its wildlife and residents. In April 2003, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency issued an assessment of the impact of the proposed mining operations on fisheries, wildlife, and native Alaska tribes.<ref>[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] [http://www2.epa.gov/bristolbay Proposal to Protect the Bristol Bay Watershed]</ref> Between 2014 and May 2017, Pebble sued the EPA several times. The company argued the EPA unfairly assumed the scope of the mine before it formally filed mining plans. Northern Dynasty Minerals LLC. accused the government agency of colluding with anti-mine activists to reach its conclusions.<ref>http://www.akbizmag.com/Alaska-Business-Monthly/November-2017/Pebble-Mine-Update/</ref>\n\nOn July 30th 2019, the EPA withdrew their preemptive proposed determination to restrict use of the pebble deposit area as a disposal site.<ref>https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-withdraws-outdated-preemptive-proposed-determination-restrict-use-pebble-deposit</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bristol Bay Borough]]\n*[[Lake and Peninsula Borough]]\n*[[Naknek, Alaska]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bristol Bay}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051107073559/http://www.naco.org/Template.cfm?Section=Find_a_County&Template=%2Fcffiles%2Fcounties%2Fcounty.cfm&id=2164 Lake & Peninsula Borough]\n*[http://www.theborough.com/ Bristol Bay Borough]\n*[http://www.lpsd.com/ Lake and Peninsula School District]\n*[http://www.bristolbayalliance.com/ Bristol Bay Alliance]\n*[http://www.bbna.com Bristol Bay Native Association]\n*[http://www.savebristolbay.org Save Bristol Bay]\n*[http://www.renewableresourcescoalition.org Renewable Resources Coalition]\n*[http://www.bristolbaywild.com Bristol Bay Wild]\n*[http://www.pebblewatch.com Pebble Watch by Bristol Bay Native Corporation]\n*[https://archives-manuscripts.dartmouth.edu/repositories/2/resources/1014 Arnold Haverlee Manuscripts] at Dartmouth College Library\n\n=== Technical reports ===\n*[http://library.state.ak.us/asp/edocs/2007/04/ocn131417018.pdf  Abundance, age, sex, and size statistics for Pacific herring in the Togiak district of Bristol Bay, 2004 / by Chuck Brazil.] Hosted by the [https://web.archive.org/web/20071012120420/http://library.state.ak.us/asp/ Alaska State Publications Program]\n*[https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo6530 Mineral Investigations in the Bristol Bay Mining District Study Area, Southwest Alaska] [[Bureau of Land Management]]\n\n{{coord|57|40|N|159|50|W|dim:500000_region:US-AK_type:waterbody|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bays of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Bristol Bay Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Dillingham Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bays of the Bering Sea]]\n", "text_old": "[[File:Bristol Bay.png|thumb|upright=1.15|Map of Bristol Bay]]\n[[File:BristolBay2.jpg|thumb|[[Packraft]]s on Nushagak Bay]]\n[[File:Bristol Bay Fisherman.jpg|thumb|Bristol Bay fisherman]]\n'''Bristol Bay''' (''Iilgayaq'' in [[Yupik language|Central Yup'ik]], {{lang-ru|\u0417\u0430\u043b\u0438\u0432 \u0411\u0440\u0438\u0441\u0442\u043e\u043b\u044c\u0441\u043a\u0438\u0439}}<ref>[https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/c/c8/Alaska_1844.jpg \u041a\u0430\u0440\u0442\u0430 \u041b\u0435\u0434\u043e\u0432\u0438\u0442\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043c\u043e\u0440\u044f \u0438 \u0412\u043e\u0441\u0442\u043e\u0447\u043d\u043e\u0433\u043e \u043e\u043a\u0435\u0430\u043d\u0430 (1844)]</ref>) is the eastern-most arm of the [[Bering Sea]], at 57\u00b0 to 59\u00b0 North 157\u00b0 to 162\u00b0 West in [[Southwest Alaska]]. Bristol Bay is 400&nbsp;km (250&nbsp;mi) long and 290&nbsp;km, (180&nbsp;mi) wide at its mouth.  A number of rivers flow into the bay, including the [[Cinder River|Cinder]], [[Egegik River|Egegik]], [[Igushik River|Igushik]], [[Kvichak River|Kvichak]], [[Meshik River|Meshik]], [[Nushagak River|Nushagak]], [[Naknek River|Naknek]], [[Togiak River|Togiak]], and [[Ugashik River|Ugashik]].\n\nUpper reaches of Bristol Bay experience some of the highest tides in the world.  One such reach, the [[Nushagak Bay]] near [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]] and another near [[Naknek, Alaska|Naknek]] in [[Kvichak Bay]] have tidal extremes in excess of 10&nbsp;m (30&nbsp; ft), ranking them &mdash; and the area &mdash; as eighth highest in the world.  Coupled with the extreme number of shoals, sandbars, and shallows, makes navigation troublesome, especially during the area's frequently strong winds. As the shallowest part of the Bering Sea, Bristol Bay is one of the most dangerous regions for large vessels.\n\n<!--  These features are one reason why the Bristol Bay commercial salmon fishing fleet is limited to 32-foot (10 m) overall keel length.{{Fact|date=September 2008}} Also, most of the area is not well documented by nautical charts and navigational aids are sparse.{{Fact|date=September 2008}} I removed this section to the discussion page for further debate and to dispute this \"fact.\"  I'm from Bristol Bay, and there is no citation included in this \"fact,\" which I believe to be false.  ~~~~ -->\n\n== History ==\n[[File:BristolBay3.jpg|thumb|Tundra landscape near Bristol Bay]]\nIn ancient times, much of Bristol Bay was dry and arable, along with much of the [[Bering land bridge|Bering Sea Land Bridge]].  More recently, its proximity to mineral, animal and seafood riches provided an incentive for human habitation along its shoreline. Early Russian and English exploration provided most of the non-native influences of the area. During his voyage through the area in 1778, the famed British navigator and explorer, Captain [[James Cook]] named the area \"in honor of the [[Augustus Hervey, 3rd Earl of Bristol|Admiral Earl of Bristol]]\" in England.\n\n=== Early settlement ===\n[[File:BristolBay4.jpg|thumb|left|upright|Shore of Bristol Bay]]\nAfter establishing some temporary settlements in the late 1790s, The [[Russian American Company]] sent exploratory parties to document the coast and nearby inland areas of Bristol Bay. One of these charted the area between the [[Kuskokwim River|Kuskokwim]] and [[Nushagak River]]s. The original Eskimo village at Naknek went through various names as recorded by the Russians after they arrived in the area in 1819 (1821-\u201cNaugeik\u201d; 1880- \u201cKinuyak\u201d; and finally Naknek as named by Russian Navy Captain Tebenkov). Later, in 1819, an [[Aleut people|Aleut]] by the name of Andrei Ustiugov drew the first intensive charts of Bristol Bay.  Additionally, ships of the [[Russian Navy]] conducted extensive surveys of the Bering Sea coastline into the mid-19th century, naming many of the geographical features commonly used today: Capes Constantine, Chichagof, Menshikof and Greig, Mounts [[Veniaminof]] and [[Mount Pavlof|Pavlof]], [[Becharof Lake]], etc. In 1883 the first salmon cannery was open in Bristol Bay\u201d <ref>https://www.nps.gov/lacl/learn/historyculture/upload/Canneries-Cabins-Caches-508-compliant-Sept-2015-low-res.pdf</ref> (Source information from the cannery article to give context on the expansion of the salmon industry in Alaska and the history of growth.\n\nThe influence of the Katmai Volcano Explosion in 1912 and the influenza epidemic in 1919 decimated the Naknek people and area. According to oral history, there were only about three original families left at that time.<ref>(https://www.nps.gov/lacl/learn/historyculture/upload/Canneries-Cabins-Caches-508-compliant-Sept-2015-low-res.pdf)</ref>\n\n=== World War Two ===\nOn July 7,{{Clarify|reason=what year?|date=June 2019}} Alaskans witnessed conflict as Japanese fishing vessels entered the waters of Bristol Bay with 10,000-ton fishing trawlers to harvest salmon.\n\nAt that time, the Fisheries Bureau prohibited the use of motorized vessels, fish traps, and purse seines in Alaska. This was to ensure a 50% escapement of the spawning salmon, to guarantee their sustainability.\n\nThe Japanese fleet was composed of diesel-powered steel vessels. The Japanese had a technological advantage over the American fisherman and dominated the bay that summer.\n\nIn 1938, the United States agreed with Japan that the Japanese would refrain from fishing in Alaskan waters. This agreement was honored until Japan and the United States entered World War 2. In the 1950s, Japan was strengthening its fishing presence in the Pacific; the US, Canada, and Japan passed the North Pacific Fisheries Treaty. This treaty managed the resources of the region jointly to preserve the future generations of fish. This agreement is the model for international fisheries regulations today.<ref>http://www.visitbristolbay.com/visitor-guide/cultures.html</ref>\n\n== Industry ==\n[[File:BristolBay5.jpg|thumb|Nushagak River, draining into Bristol Bay]]\n\nBristol Bay is home to the world's most abundant [[sockeye salmon]] [[fishery]] as well as strong runs of chum salmon, silver salmon, and king salmon, each occurring seasonally.<ref>La Ganga, Maria L. (December 16, 2014) [http://www.latimes.com/nation/la-na-bristol-bay-leases-20141216-story.html \"Obama protects Alaska's Bristol Bay from oil and gas drilling\"] ''[[Los Angeles Times]]''</ref>  Kings are usually the first to run up the river followed by reds and chums.  Silvers and Pinks are the last to run up the river.\nOn an international scale, sockeye salmon are a relatively rare creature. Like other wild salmon species, sockeye harvests fluctuate but comprise 4 to 7 percent of global salmon production and 13 to 20 percent of native salmon harvests. Between 2011 and 2014, sockeye accounted for 5 percent of the world's salmon harvest by volume and 15 percent of the world's wild salmon harvest.\n\n===Commercial fishing===\nBristol Bay is home to the world's largest salmon run. All five Eastern Pacific species spawn in the bay's freshwater tributaries. Commercial fisheries include the world's largest sockeye salmon fishery.<ref>http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/index.cfm?adfg=commercialbyareabristolbay.main</ref> The Kvijack drains from Lake Iliamna, which is downstream of the deposit. Along with herring and other fisheries, salmon account for nearly 75% of local jobs.\n\nDuring the first 50 years of commercial salmon fishing in Bristol Bay, the fishing boats were restricted to sail power. When this restriction lifted in 1951, it took only seven short years to outfit all the boats (approximately 1,500) with diesel or gas engines. In the late 1920s another law was passed restricting the length of the boats to 32 feet. This law holds true even today.<ref>http://www.adfg.alaska.gov/index.cfm?adfg=commercialbyareabristolbay.main</ref>\n\n=== Canneries ===\nBristol Bay is a remote part of Alaska. The canneries preserve the freshness of the salmon which are gutted, cleaned, and processed on site. These companies have established a presence in Bristol Bay.\n\nCanneries include North Pacific Seafoods,Togiak Seafoods, Bristol Bay Setnet, Friedman Family Fisheries, Peter Pan Seafoods, Ekuk Fisheries, Big Creek Shore plant, Coffee Point Seafood, Icicle Seafoods, Wild Premium Salmon, Seafood Enterprises of Alaska, Alaska General Seafoods, Alaska Salmon Wild, Da Kine Enterprise, Extreme Salmon, Great Ruby Fish, My Girl, Naknek Family Fisheries, North Pacific Seafoods, Ocean Beauty, Silver Bay Seafoods, Trident Seafoods, Tulchina Fisheries, Diamond Lodge Smokehouse, and Nakeen Homepack.\n\n[[File:Bristol Bay shore.jpg|thumb|left|Shore of Bristol Bay near [[Naknek, Alaska|Naknek]]]]\nMajor industries are [[commercial fishing]] and the associated canneries, [[sport fishing]], [[hunting]] and [[tourism]].  The number of business lodges, hunting- and fishing-resorts and visitors to the nearby [[Katmai National Park and Preserve]] has grown exponentially in recent years. Sports fishing is another important local industry. Many lodges cater to sport fishermen targeting the salmon and trout populations in the freshwater tributaries. Freshwater species include humpback whitefish (Coregonus pidschianpp), Dolly Varden trout (Salvelinus malma), and Rainbow trout (Oncorhynchus mykiss).[18]\n\nThe area has also experienced significant interest in oil and mineral development, most notably with the proposed [[Pebble Mine]] on the north shore of [[Iliamna Lake]], and auctioning of leases to tracts in the southern Bristol Bay area known as the [[North Aleutians Basin]], an area which has been closed to offshore oil and gas development since a moratorium in 1998.  The draft plan by the [[Bureau of Land Management]] (pending public comments until 2/5/2007), also proposes to open most of the BLM's {{convert|3600000|acres}} in the area to [[Underground mining (hard rock)|hard rock mining]] and oil and gas drilling.\n\n== Demographics ==\n[[File:BristolBay1.jpg|thumb|upright|Abandoned cabin on Bristol Bay]]\nThe three largest communities of the Bristol Bay area are [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]], [[King Salmon, Alaska|King Salmon]], and [[Naknek, Alaska|Naknek]].  Smaller communities which dot the coastline and rivers of Bristol Bay include: [[Egegik, Alaska|Egegik]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u026a|\u0261|\u025b|\u0261|\u026a|k}}, [[Ekuk, Alaska|Ekuk]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|k|o\u028a|k}}, [[Igiugig, Alaska|Igiugig]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|\u025b|d\u0292|i\u02d0|\u02c8|j|\u0254\u02d0|\u0261|\u026a|\u0261}},{{Dubious|date=May 2009}} [[Manokotak, Alaska|Manokotak]] {{IPAc-en|m|\u0251\u02d0|n|\u0259|\u02c8|k|o\u028a|t|\u0251\u02d0|k}}, [[New Stuyahok, Alaska|New Stuyahok]] {{IPAc-en|\u02c8|s|t|u\u02d0|j|\u0259|h|\u0252|k}}, [[Newhalen, Alaska|Newhalen]], [[Nondalton, Alaska|Nondalton]], [[Pilot Point, Alaska|Pilot Point]], [[Port Heiden, Alaska|Port Heiden]], [[Ugashik, Alaska|Ugashik]] ({{IPAc-en|j|u\u02d0|\u02c8|\u0261|\u00e6|\u0283|\u026a|k}}, and South Naknek.\n\nAll of these communities are primarily inhabited by [[Alaska Natives]], except for [[Dillingham, Alaska|Dillingham]] and [[King Salmon, Alaska|King Salmon]]; the former being influenced early-on by white salmon-cannery employees of European descent and the latter being heavily populated by military personnel stationed, primarily during Cold War years, at the nearby King Salmon Air Force Station and later by visitors and employees of the nearby [[Katmai National Park and Preserve]].\n\n== Proposed Pebble Mine ==\n{{Main|Pebble Mine}}\nA mineral exploration project investigating a large [[porphyry copper]], [[gold]], and [[molybdenum]] deposit in the Bristol Bay region has been proposed and may be undertaken by British-Australian<ref>http://www.riotinto.com/documents/140415_Rio_Tinto_delivers_strong_first_quarter_production.pdf</ref> [[Rio Tinto Group]] and Japanese <ref>https://www.nrdc.org/stories/crushing-alaskas-pebble-mine</ref> [[Conglomerate (company)|conglomerate]] [[Mitsubishi]]. Northern Dynasty Minerals LLC staked a claim on the site in 2001 and with its partners, invested 500 million dollars into the project. The mining company lost all of its partners in 2011 due to increasing government regulations and distrust by its partners.\n\nBecause of the estimated 10 billion tons of mining waste that must be permanently stored in the area, which is an active earthquake zone, and Rio Tinto's environmental track record, which is seen as poor by many environmental advocacy groups, fears have been raised about the potential impact on the Bristol Bay area and its wildlife and residents. In April 2003, the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency issued an assessment of the impact of the proposed mining operations on fisheries, wildlife, and native Alaska tribes.<ref>[[United States Environmental Protection Agency]] [http://www2.epa.gov/bristolbay Proposal to Protect the Bristol Bay Watershed]</ref> Between 2014 and May 2017, Pebble sued the EPA several times. The company argued the EPA unfairly assumed the scope of the mine before it formally filed mining plans. Northern Dynasty Minerals LLC. accused the government agency of colluding with anti-mine activists to reach its conclusions.<ref>http://www.akbizmag.com/Alaska-Business-Monthly/November-2017/Pebble-Mine-Update/</ref>\n\nOn July 30th 2019, the EPA withdrew their preemptive proposed determination to restrict use of the pebble deposit area as a disposal site.<ref>https://www.epa.gov/newsreleases/epa-withdraws-outdated-preemptive-proposed-determination-restrict-use-pebble-deposit</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n*[[Bristol Bay Borough]]\n*[[Lake and Peninsula Borough]]\n*[[Naknek, Alaska]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Commons category|Bristol Bay}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20051107073559/http://www.naco.org/Template.cfm?Section=Find_a_County&Template=%2Fcffiles%2Fcounties%2Fcounty.cfm&id=2164 Lake & Peninsula Borough]\n*[http://www.theborough.com/ Bristol Bay Borough]\n*[http://www.lpsd.com/ Lake and Peninsula School District]\n*[http://www.bristolbayalliance.com/ Bristol Bay Alliance]\n*[http://www.bbna.com Bristol Bay Native Association]\n*[http://www.savebristolbay.org Save Bristol Bay]\n*[http://www.renewableresourcescoalition.org Renewable Resources Coalition]\n*[http://www.bristolbaywild.com Bristol Bay Wild]\n*[http://www.pebblewatch.com Pebble Watch by Bristol Bay Native Corporation]\n\n=== Technical reports ===\n*[http://library.state.ak.us/asp/edocs/2007/04/ocn131417018.pdf  Abundance, age, sex, and size statistics for Pacific herring in the Togiak district of Bristol Bay, 2004 / by Chuck Brazil.] Hosted by the [https://web.archive.org/web/20071012120420/http://library.state.ak.us/asp/ Alaska State Publications Program]\n*[https://purl.fdlp.gov/GPO/gpo6530 Mineral Investigations in the Bristol Bay Mining District Study Area, Southwest Alaska] [[Bureau of Land Management]]\n\n{{coord|57|40|N|159|50|W|dim:500000_region:US-AK_type:waterbody|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Bays of Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Bristol Bay Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Dillingham Census Area, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bodies of water of Lake and Peninsula Borough, Alaska]]\n[[Category:Bays of the Bering Sea]]\n", "name_user": "Igrallert", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:added link", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bristol_Bay"}
{"title_page": "Che\u0142mno trials", "text_new": "{{Infobox court case\n|italic title=no\n| name         = Che\u0142mno trials\n| image        = Sad Apelacyjny Lodz.jpg\n| imagesize    = 265\n| caption      = The [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] courthouse, built in 1927\u201332 during the [[Polish culture in the Interbellum|Poland's Interbellum]].<ref name=\"courthouse\">{{cite web | url=http://www.lodz.so.gov.pl/index.php?id=352&id2=408 | title=S\u0105d Okr\u0119gowy w \u0141odzi (The \u0141\u00f3d\u017a courthouse) | publisher=Strona BIP S\u0105du Okr\u0119gowego w \u0141odzi | work=Historia (History) | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-15 | author=BIP}}</ref> Location of the first trial, 2007 photo. \n| SubmitDate   = May 24, 1945, [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] \n| date_decided = Last case: 1965, [[Cologne]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Che\u0142mno trials''' were a series of consecutive [[war-crime]] trials of the [[Che\u0142mno extermination camp]] personnel, held in [[Poland]] and in [[Germany]] following [[World War II]]. The cases were decided almost twenty years apart. The first judicial trial of the former ''SS'' men \u2013 members of the ''[[Schutzstaffel#SS units and branches|SS-Sonderkommando]] [[Che\u0142mno nad Nerem|Kulmhof]]'' \u2013 took place in 1945 at the District Court in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], Poland. The subsequent four trials, held in [[Bonn]], Germany, began in 1962 and concluded three years later, in 1965 in [[Cologne]].\n\nA number of camp officials, gas-van operators and ''SS'' guards, were arraigned before the court on charges of war crimes and crimes against humanity committed at [[Che\u0142mno extermination camp|Che\u0142mno]] (a.k.a. ''Kulmhof'') in [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|occupied Poland]] in the period between December 1941 and January 1945. The evidence against the accused, including testimonies by surviving witnesses, former prisoners, and mechanics attending to repair needs of the ''SS'', was examined in Poland by Judge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz of the \u0141\u00f3d\u017a District Court (''S\u0105d Okr\u0119gowy w \u0141odzi'').{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=02ABWyc_Ks0C&pg=PA208&dq=%22testimonies+collected+by+Judge+Bednarz%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7N6UUZ2vMKLCyQGW6oH4DQ&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22testimonies%20collected%20by%20Judge%20Bednarz%22&f=false The Gas Vans (Appendix I), pp. 206&ndash;209]}} Three convicted defendants were sentenced to death,<ref name=\"UMD\" /> including the camp deputy commandant ''[[Oberscharf\u00fchrer]]'' Walter Piller (wrongly, Filer); the [[Nazi gas van|gas van]] operator ''[[Hauptscharf\u00fchrer]]'' Hermann Gielow (Gilow), as well as Bruno Israel from [[Ordnungspolizei|Order Police]] (his sentence was commuted to life). All three were members of the ''SS Special Detachment Kulmhof'' responsible for the extermination of Jews and non-Jews, during [[the Holocaust in Poland|the Holocaust in occupied Poland]].{{sfn | Montague| 2012 |loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=02ABWyc_Ks0C&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151&dq=Walter+Piller,+Hermann+Gielow,+SS-Sonderkommando+Kulmhof&source=bl&ots=3-lUGRISPS&sig=PY1Y-U8wOGDkYi6gYaVp0wLhwIk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3OWUUfPSHY-byAHlyYGADQ&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Walter%20Piller%2C%20Hermann%20Gielow%2C%20SS-Sonderkommando%20Kulmhof&f=false Extermination, pp. 151&ndash;152]}}\n\nIn the years 1962\u201365, a dozen ''SS''-men from Kulmhof were arraigned before the German court (''Landgericht'') in [[Bonn]], RFN. They were charged with the murder of 180,000 Jews in the camp.<ref name=\"JTA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/1963/01/22/archive/jewish-survivors-of-chelmno-camp-testify-at-trial-of-guards |title=Jewish Survivors of Chelmno Camp Testify at Trial of Guards |publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |work=JTA Archive |date=January 22, 1963 |accessdate=2013-05-17 |author=JTA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220122211/http://www.jta.org/1963/01/22/archive/jewish-survivors-of-chelmno-camp-testify-at-trial-of-guards |archivedate=2014-02-20 }}</ref> The jury deliberations continued for three years, with sentences ranging from 13 years' imprisonment to 13 months and 2 weeks. Half of the defendants were cleared of all charges and released by Germany.<ref name=\"poznan.jewish.org\" /><ref name=\"Lichtenstein\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fluchschrift.net/verbrech/november/011141.htm | title=01.11.1941. Errichtung des ersten Vernichtungslagers in Chelmno | publisher=Fluchschrift - Deutsche Verbrechen | work=Heiner Lichtenstein, Daten aus der Zeitgeschichte, in: Trib\u00fcne Nr. 179/2006 | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-17 | author=Fluchschrift}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n| direction=vertical\n| header=The case of the Che\u0142mno death camp\n| header_background=#AFCFDE\n| width=270\n| image1=Che\u0142mno (Kulmhof) 1942 (Ko\u0142o).jpg\n| caption1=Deportation to Che\u0142mno. In this photo, loading of victims sent from the [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto|ghetto in \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]\n| image2=Children headed for deportation.JPG\n| caption2=[[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto|Ghetto]] children rounded up for deportation to Che\u0142mno\n| image3=Destroyed Magirus-Deutz furniture transport van Kolno Poland 1945.jpg\n| caption3=A model of Magirus-Deutz gas van used for suffocation at the [[Che\u0142mno extermination camp]]. This particular van has not been modified, nevertheless it gives a good idea about the process\n| image4=PikiWiki Israel 7036 Chelmno extermination camp burial pits.jpg\n| caption4=Archeological excavations at the forest ''Waldlager'' camp where the corpses were cremated on rails, ashes cooled and shovelled into sacks to be trucked to the nearby river at night\n}}\n\n==1945 Che\u0142mno Trial in Poland==\nAfter liberation by the Soviet Army, the new government of Poland began its official investigation into the Che\u0142mno war crimes on May 24, 1945.<ref name=\"Montague-177\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=Wladyslaw+Bednarz+1945&source=bl&ots=XK4QuNgEtL&sig=CmzFgr_M78CfuKcW3FAbwPZe_f8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NJ2SUby7O-rVigLy5oC4CQ&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Wladyslaw%20Bednarz%201945&f=false | title=Epilogue (Judge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz) | publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press | work=Chelmno and the Holocaust: The History of Hitler's First Death Camp | date=Mar 15, 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Patrick Montague | page=177 | isbn=0807869414}}</ref> Although most Germans fled, Piller and Gielow were soon captured by the Soviets and brought back.{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA184&dq=%22on+June+6,+1945,+the+Polish+government+began+its+own+investigation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EJCXUYXwOIiviQLD4YCYBA&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22on%20June%206%2C%201945%2C%20the%20Polish%20government%20began%20its%20own%20investigation%22&f=false Epilogue, pp. 184&ndash;193]}}\n\nNotably, the trial of [[List of major perpetrators of the Holocaust|Holocaust perpetrators]] from Che\u0142mno was unlike any other war-crimes trial, because the camp had been essentially eradicated by the [[SS]], along with most traces of the mass murder. Truckloads of ashes of its victims were dumped in the [[Warta]] river daily, the \"palace\" was blown up with rubble removed to foundations, [[Nazi gas van|mobile gas-chambers]] and loot were driven back to Berlin, written records were destroyed, including train departure records. There was nothing to see for the commissars, or draw interest.<ref name=\"ushmm.org-Chelmno\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005194 | title=Chelmno | publisher=Copyright \u00a9 United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, Washington, DC | work=Holocaust Encyclopedia | date=May 11, 2012 | accessdate=May 18, 2013 | author=USHMM | format=permission granted to be reused, in whole or in part, on Wikipedia; [[OTRS]] ticket no. 2007071910012533 confirmed | quote=''Text from USHMM has been released under the [[GFDL]].''}}</ref> Some of the key evidence was mistakenly discarded in the trash in 1945 (i.e. over 5,000 pairs of damaged shoes from a destroyed synagogue in [[Ko\u0142o, \u0141\u00f3d\u017a Voivodeship|Ko\u0142o]]), or hauled away as usable materials, including wooden fencing and cremation grids; few people were aware of its importance.<ref name=\"Montague-177\" /> By comparison, other former [[death camp]]s were overflowing with direct evidence of war-crimes, as in the case of the [[Majdanek Trials|Majdanek trial]] decided several months before.<ref name=\"Majdanek-1 YV\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/microsoft%20word%20-%206622.pdf |title=Majdanek |publisher=Yad Vashem |work=Majdanek concentration camp |year=2007 |accessdate=2013-04-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127031515/http://www1.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/microsoft%20word%20-%206622.pdf |archivedate=November 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nJudge Bednarz soon ordered excavation of the waste in a ''Schlosslager'' burn pit. About 24,200 spoons, 4,500 knives, and 2,500 forks were found, among pots, pans, eyeglasses and many other half-burned items in the debris.<ref name=\"Montague-177\" /> It was also known that most of the victims were Jews from the [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto]], where chronicles of ghetto operations were found; in addition, non-Jewish Poles, Soviet prisoners, about 5,000 Gypsies, and whole transports of children had been deported to Che\u0142mno where they were murdered. The SS Master Sergeant Walter Piller testified about the final phase of the camp operation, including 1944 deportations from \u0141\u00f3d\u017a.<ref name=\"Jacob\">{{cite web | url=http://sunday-news.wider-des-vergessens.de/?tag=walter-piller | title=\"Walter Piller\". Ein SS-M\u00f6rder \u00fcber die Ermordung Tausender Juden | publisher=Sunday news. Das Online Magazin | work=Das ehemalige Vernichtungslager Che\u0142mno | date=28 December 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-17 | author=Rena Jacob | language=German | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716214936/http://sunday-news.wider-des-vergessens.de/?tag=walter-piller | archive-date=16 July 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> To circumvent the Nazi destruction of records and evidence, Judge Bednarz used \u0141\u00f3d\u017a ghetto records and estimates to arrive at the number of victims. Based on ghetto statistics together with testimonies, he estimated some 350,000 victims. He did not account for the period of camp inactivity.{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA184&dq=%22on+June+6,+1945,+the+Polish+government+began+its+own+investigation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EJCXUYXwOIiviQLD4YCYBA&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22on%20June%206%2C%201945%2C%20the%20Polish%20government%20began%20its%20own%20investigation%22&f=false Epilogue, p. 184]}} The range of estimated victims presented at the 1962 trial in Bonn was 180,000 with 152,000 as the lowest acceptable number.<ref name=\"zchor.org\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zchor.org/CHELMSUM.HTM | title=Review: Death Camp: \"Chelmno upon Ner\", Summary | publisher=We Remember | work=Janusz Gulczy\u0144ski: \"Ob\u00f3z \u015bmierci w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem\" (1991) | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Ada Holtzman}}</ref>\n\nThe first Che\u0142mno trial in Poland established many critical details from the camp history, but also revealed the operation of mobile [[gas chamber]]s, which used exhaust fumes as the killing agent, diverted into sheet metal-lined vans. The names of SS officials and commanders at the camp were established, including the ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Herbert Lange]] and the ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Hans Johann Bothmann|Hans Bothmann]] who had vanished.<ref name=\"zchor.org\" />{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA175&dq=%22Sonderkommando+fled%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cX6fUYS5Osm3iwKr0YDQDQ&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Sonderkommando%20fled%22&f=false Epilogue, p. 175]}}\n\n===Survivor testimonies===\nJudge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz, assisted by the Deputy Recording Clerk, heard testimonies of key witnesses including [[Simon Srebnik|Szymon (Simon) Srebrnik]] (age fifteen), who survived being shot in the head during the Germans' last execution of Jews at the camp, and [[Mordecha\u00ef Podchlebnik|Micha\u0142 (Mordecha\u00ef) Podchlebnik]], who escaped in 1942 into the surrounding forest from the burial ''[[Sonderkommando]]''. Podchlebnik testified on June 9, 1945. He was at the camp for 10 days digging mass graves in January 1942 at the time of the Nazi ''[[Operation Reinhard|Aktion Reinhard]]''. The cremation process was implemented there a year later.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-podchlebnik\" />\n\n{{quote|I figured that about 1,000 people were gassed every day... which filled three to four metres of trench... I had been trying to persuade my inmates to escape... On the way to work, I noticed that one of the windows on the bus could be lowered. I told my companion Winer from Izbica... we were separated and I had to get into the truck... I cut the tarpaulin... and jumped out of the car. They started shooting at me but all bullets missed the target. Luckily the bus did not follow the truck... After two days, during which I did not eat anything... {{grey|[}}I{{grey|]}} headed in the direction of [[Grab\u00f3w, Kutno County|Grab\u00f3w]] town. On my way I stopped at some peasant\u2019s cottages (I do not know his name). He gave me some food and a hat, shaved me and showed the way. In Grab\u00f3w I met Winer...| ''From'' [[Mordecha\u00ef Podchlebnik|Micha\u0142 Podchlebnik]], ''Chelmno Survivor Testimony''.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-podchlebnik\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/survivor/podchlebnik.html | title=Michal Podchlebnik, Chelmno Survivor Testimony | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Chelmno Survivor Testimony | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Chris Webb, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>}}\n\nThe second survivor from the Jewish ''Sonderkommando'', [[Simon Srebnik|Szymon Srebrnik]], was from \u0141\u00f3d\u017a and 15 years old at the end of the war. He testified on June 29, 1945 in [[Ko\u0142o]]; he was not under oath, although informed of criminal liability for a false statement. Srebnik worked at the forest camp during the second extermination phase, when the bodies were cremated after being delivered in the gas-vans.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-srebrnik\" />\n\n{{quote|In March 1944... we were in the ''Sonderkommando'' camp... The stronger and better workers were sent to the woods... The ''Waldkommando'' consisted of about 40 Jews... We were all shackled... The furnaces were very primitive, they stood on a cement foundation... They were approximately three metres (10 feet) tall. The width was about the same. The fire grate was made of narrow-gauge railroad railings... The capacity of one furnace was more or less the same as one [[Nazi gas van|van]]... It took approximately one hour for the corpses to burn. Then a new pile of bodies were added... While the clothes were being sorted, high ranking SS-men came and chose something for themselves...| ''From'' [[Simon Srebnik|Szymon Srebrnik]], ''Chelmno Survivor Testimony''.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-srebrnik\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/survivor/srebrnik.html | title=Szymon Srebrnik, Chelmno Survivor Testimony | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Chelmno Survivor Testimony | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Chris Webb, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>}}\n\n===The defendants===\nOn October 29/30, 1945 Judge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz questioned German ''Oberwachtmeister'' Bruno Israel (born Bruno Koenig), employed at the final phase of the Che\u0142mno extermination. He was accused of committing crimes against the Polish nation under the PKWN Decree of August 31, 1944 pertaining to Nazi War Criminals (the so-called ''[[:pl:Sierpni\u00f3wka|Sierpni\u00f3wka]].'' This provided for the death penalty without direct appeal).<ref name=\"DU-1944\">{{cite web | url=http://static1.money.pl/d/akty_prawne/pdf/DU/1946/69/DU19460690377.pdf | title=Dekret Polskiego Komitetu Wyzwolenia Narodowego z dnia 31 sierpnia 1944 | publisher=Internetowy System Akt\u00f3w Prawnych | work=Dziennik Ustaw Nr 69. Poz. 377. Zalacznik. | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-19 | author=ISAP | format=PDF file, direct download 110 KB}}</ref> The defendant claimed to be not guilty.\n\nBruno Israel testified the following:  \n{{quote|In July or August 1944... I was assigned to the ''Sonderkommando Kulmhof''... I took part in the escorting of the transports. When Jews asked where they were being taken, I answered... they were going to work. The Jews generally believed it and behaved peacefully... They were given soap, unless they had their own. They were told they would get towels at the bath-house. Then all of them, both men and women were herded into a corral at the exit of which there was a ''[[Nazi gas van|Sonderwagen]]'' (the van)... The [dead] bodies were thrown into one of the [''Waldlager''] crematoriums. The furnaces were about 10 meters wide and about 5-6 meters long. They did not stick out above the ground level. They had no chimneys.| ''Oberwachtmeister'' Bruno Israel, ''Chelmno Defendant Testimony''.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-3\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/trials/chelmnowachmeister.html | title=Bruno Israel, Chelmno Wachtmeister - Testimony | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Trials. Protocol of the Interrogation | year=2009 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Victor Smart,  H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>}}\n\nAlthough Bruno Israel was convicted of war crimes and sentenced to death, the Polish President [[Boles\u0142aw Bierut]] granted him clemency in September 1946, commuting his sentence to life. Israel was released conditionally for five years in November 1958, and was never required to return to prison.<ref name=\"UMD\" />\n\nStatutory death sentences were given to other two defendants, who were found guilty. Both Walter Piller and Hermann Gielow applied for a presidential pardon, which they were not granted. After a few years spent on [[death row]], Walter Piller was executed on January 19, 1949. Herman Gielow was executed in the [[Pozna\u0144]] prison on June 6, 1951.<ref name=\"UMD\" /> The very Decree of August 31, 1944 used in their sentencing was amended in December 1946, making the laws ''not applicable'' from the outset, in connection with the [[World War II crimes in Poland#The Soviet occupation|Soviet World War II crimes in Poland]].<ref name=\"DU-1944\" />\n\n==Che\u0142mno Trials in Germany 1962\u201365==\nEleven indicted suspects from Che\u0142mno were arraigned at the Special Criminal Court in [[Bonn]], RFN (''Landgericht Bonn'') in 1962\u201365 on charges of complicity to the murder of 180,000 Jews.<ref name=\"UMD\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gminadabie.pl/asp/pl_start.asp?typ=14&sub=283&menu=209&strona=1 | title=SS-Sonderkommando Kulmhof | publisher=Urz\u0105d Miejski w D\u0105biu (homepage) | work=Oddzia\u0142 Specjalny Kulmhof | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-16 | author=UMD}}</ref> A total of four trials were held. Later observers referred to at least one of them as a ''judicial farce''.<ref name=\"Lichtenstein\" /> Genocide was not in the criminal code of Nazi Germany and the court ruled that it could not be applied retroactively. Depositions were not sufficient to secure convictions. There was little physical evidence remaining at the crime scene. No victims' bodies to examine: their ashes had been carried downriver and out to sea.<ref name=\"JTA\" /><ref name=\"preventgenocide\">{{cite web | url=http://www.preventgenocide.org/punish/domestic/ | title=Paragraph \u00a7220a (genocide) of Germany's Strafgesetzbuch | publisher=Prevent Genocide International | work=Genocide and international crimes in domestic courts. Chapter: Germany | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-20 | author=PGI}}</ref>\n\nThe most severe penalties of 15 years were given to Gustav Laabs, ''SS Hauptscharf\u00fchrer'', a gas van operator, and Alois H\u00e4fele, ''SS Untersturmf\u00fchrer,'' a camp ''Hauskommando'' leader. The latter's sentence was reduced by two years on appeal because he reportedly gave cigarettes to some of the walking dead. Half of the defendants were cleared of all charges and released.<ref name=\"UMD\" /><ref name=\"poznan.jewish.org\">{{cite web | url=http://poznan.jewish.org.pl/index.php/zaglada/Osrodek-Zaglady-w-Chelmnie-nad-Nerem-Kulmhof.html | title=O\u015brodek Zag\u0142ady w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem (Kulmhof) | publisher=Poznanska Filia Zwiazku Gmin Wyznaniowych Zydowskich w RP | work=Holokaust | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-05-15 | author=Wojciech Meixner}}</ref> ''Oberscharf\u00fchrer'' Gustaw Fiedler, from ''Polizeiwachtkommando,'' was tried in 1965 in [[Cologne]] and sentenced to 13\u00bd months imprisonment.\n\n::{| width=\"98%\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"font-size: 90%; border: gray solid 1px; border-collapse: collapse; text-align: middle;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|#\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Defendant <ref name=\"UMD\" />\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Born <ref name=\"AHF\" />\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Rank <ref name=\"AHF\">{{cite web | url=http://forum.axishistory.com/viewtopic.php?f=38&t=3031 | title=Chelmno Personnel | publisher=Axis History Forum | work=The Phil Nix SS & Polizei section | accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref>\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Function\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Sentence <ref name=\"UMD\" />\n|-\n|1||Gustaw Laabs||20 December 1902||''SS Hauptscharf\u00fchrer''||Gas-van operator||{{space|3}} 15 years imprisonment \n|-\n|2||Walter Burmeister||2 May 1906||''SS Unterscharf\u00fchrer''||Bothmann adjutant||{{space|3}} 13 years imprisonment\n|-\n|3||Alois H\u00e4fele||5 July 1893||''SS Untersturmf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp ''Hauskommando'' leader||{{space|3}} 15 years imprisonment \n|-\n|4||Kurt M\u00f6bius||3 May 1895||''SS Scharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} 8 years imprisonment \n|-\n|5||Karl Heinl||11 April 1912||''SS Unterscharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} 7 years imprisonment \n|-\n|6||Walter (Ernst) Burmeister <ref name=\"Klee\">{{cite book | title=The Good Old Days | publisher=The Free Press, NY |author1=Ernst Klee |author2=W. Dressen |author3=V. Riess | year=1988 | pages=219\u2013220}}</ref>||(''ntbcw'')||''Gaswagenfahrer''||Gas-van operator||{{space|3}} 3 \u00bd years imprisonment \n|-\n|7||Heinrich Bock||16 June 1912||''SS Scharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|8||Anton Mehring||25 March 1920||''Unterscharf\u00fchrer''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|9||Aleksander Steinke||16 March 1912||''{{nobreak|Polizei-Oberwachmeister}}''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|10||Friedrich Maderholz||7 November 1919||''Hauptscharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|11||Wilhelm Heukelbach||28 February 1911||''SS Oberscharf\u00fchrer''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|12||Wilhelm Schulte||23 June 1912||''Hauptscharf\u00fchrer''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|13||Gustaw Fiedler||(''1965 trial'')||''Oberscharf\u00fchrer''||''Polizeiwachtkommando''||{{space|3}} 13 months 2 weeks imprisonment\n|-\n|}\n\nThe first camp commandant, ''SS Sturmbannf\u00fchrer'' [[Herbert Lange]], was killed in action on April 20, 1945 near Berlin. The second head of Che\u0142mno, ''Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Hans Bothmann]] who made substantial improvements to the killing method in the final phase of the camp operation, committed suicide in British custody in April 1946.<ref name=\"zchor.org\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Caa4rl8SHHwC&pg=PA338&lpg=PA338&dq=Hans+Bothmann+committed+suicide&source=bl&ots=R-ZDL2a8ij&sig=O01N_FuICGwD1eRPSdEkg5tw_0w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mXiaUamrK6jziwKc0IGQCg&ved=0CFoQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Hans%20Bothmann%20committed%20suicide&f=false | title=Two Souls in my Breast | publisher=Oxford University Press | work=Model Nazi: Arthur Greiser and the Occupation of Western Poland | date=Mar 22, 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-20 | author=Catherine Epstein | page=338 | isbn=0199646538}}</ref>\n\n==Poland 2001==\n\nThe last person charged in connection with the crimes at Che\u0142mno was a pole, Henryk Mania. He was one of eight polish prisoners who worked with the camp ''Sonderkommando''. Mania had been originally imprisoned after being accused of attempting to poison a german.<ref>[https://www.welt.de/welt_print/politik/article5364656/Eine-polnische-Parallele-zu-Demjanjuk.html Die Welt]</ref>. These eight prisoners has previously worked at a sonderkommando at [[Fort VII]] prison where they would dispose of dead prisoners. The men were then transferred to Che\u0142mno after being selected by Herbert Lange<ref name=\"seminare.pl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.seminare.pl/21/kolasa-spr1.doc | title=Mi\u0119dzynarodowa Konferencja Naukowa \"Fenomen Getta \u0141\u00f3dzkiego 1940\u20131944\" (\u0141\u00f3d\u017a 11\u201312 pa\u017adziernika 2004 r.) | publisher=Archiwum Pa\u0144stwowe w \u0141odzi (\u0141\u00f3d\u017a State Archives) | work=\u0141\u00f3d\u017a University, International \u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto Conference 2004 | year=2004 | accessdate=2013-05-23 | author1=Izabela Matysiak-Aleksandrowicz | author2=Krzysztof Kolasa | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621161038/http://seminare.pl/21/kolasa-spr1.doc | archive-date=2006-06-21 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Fifty-six years after the end of World War II, he was convicted as an accessory to murder.{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA193&dq=%2256+years+after+the+end+of+the+Second+World+War%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VJiXUc_BJeqSiQKvgYGgBg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%2256%20years%20after%20the%20end%20of%20the%20Second%20World%20War%22&f=false Epilogue, p. 193]}}.<ref>[https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/henryk-mania/ Trial International]</ref> \n\nHis investigation, begun in 1956, was renewed in 1991 by the [[Institute of National Remembrance]]. He was tried in a 2001 court case in [[Pozna\u0144]]. The [[Revolutions of 1989|collapse of the several communist/socialist governments]] and release of new records made it possible. Mania was found guilty of helping to load prisoners into gas-vans and collecting their watches and jewellery, which he also stole for himself. He was sentenced to 8 years' imprisonment, with consideration given to his advanced age.<ref name=\"\u015alusarek\">{{cite web | url=http://www.muzeum-kolo.pl/pl/images/stories/wydawnictwa-online/z-dziejow-zydow-kolskich.pdf | title=Zag\u0142ada kolskich \u017byd\u00f3w | publisher=Urz\u0105d Miejski w Kole | work=Z dziej\u00f3w \u017byd\u00f3w kolskich \u2013 w 70. rocznic\u0119 Zag\u0142ady. Sesja popularnonaukowa. Ko\u0142o 2012 | year=2012 | accessdate=2013-05-17 | author=Marta Szczesiak-\u015alusarek | page=65 | isbn=978-83-62485-66-6 | format=PDF file, direct download 855 KB | language=Polish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Auschwitz Trial]] held in [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland in 1947 against 40 SS-staff of the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] death factory\n* [[Belsen Trial]]\n* [[Belzec Trial]] before the 1st [[Munich]] District Court in the mid-1960s of the eight SS-men of the [[Belzec extermination camp]] command\n* [[Dachau Trials]], held within the walls of the former [[Dachau concentration camp]], 1945\u20131948\n* [[Majdanek Trials]], the longest Nazi war crimes trial in history, spanning over 30 years\n* [[Mauthausen-Gusen camp trials]]\n* [[Ravensbr\u00fcck Trial]]\n* [[Sobibor Trial]], held in [[Hagen]], Germany in 1965, concerning the [[Sobibor extermination camp]] officials\n* [[Treblinka trials]] in D\u00fcsseldorf, Germany\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Citation | last=Montague | first=Patrick | year=2012 | title=Che\u0142mno and the Holocaust: The History of Hitler's First Death Camp | publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]] | publication-place=Chapel Hill | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=02ABWyc_Ks0C&dq=Walter+Piller,+Hermann+Gielow,+SS-Sonderkommando+Kulmhof&source=gbs_navlinks_s | accessdate=May 24, 2013 | isbn=0807835277 | format=Google Books | quote=''Search inside.''}}\n*{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=asCq3ZD0ObQC&lpg=PA428&dq=%22the%20examining%20judge%20of%20the%20district%20court%20in%20%C5%81%C3%B3d%C5%BA%2C%20W%C5%82adys%C5%82aw%20Bednarz%22&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=Bednarz&f=false | title=Children in the Concentration Camp Universe | publisher=Rowman Altamira | work=Children during the Holocaust | date=May 31, 2011 | accessdate=2013-05-15 | author=Patricia Heberer | pages=184, 428 | isbn=0759119864}}\n*W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz, ''Ob\u00f3z strace\u0144 w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem'' with Foreword by Wac\u0142aw Barcikowski, [[Pa\u0144stwowy Instytut Wydawniczy]] PIW, Warsaw&nbsp;1946&nbsp;{{in lang|pl}}\n*Janusz Gulczy\u0144ski, ''Ob\u00f3z \u015bmierci w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem'', Wojew\u00f3dzki O\u015brodek Kultury: Muzeum Okr\u0119gowe, [[Konin]] 1991 {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chelmno extermination camp}}\n[[Category:Che\u0142mno extermination camp| ]]\n[[Category:Holocaust trials]]\n[[Category:Trials in Poland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox court case\n|italic title=no\n| name         = Che\u0142mno trials\n| image        = Sad Apelacyjny Lodz.jpg\n| imagesize    = 265\n| caption      = The [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] courthouse, built in 1927\u201332 during the [[Polish culture in the Interbellum|Poland's Interbellum]].<ref name=\"courthouse\">{{cite web | url=http://www.lodz.so.gov.pl/index.php?id=352&id2=408 | title=S\u0105d Okr\u0119gowy w \u0141odzi (The \u0141\u00f3d\u017a courthouse) | publisher=Strona BIP S\u0105du Okr\u0119gowego w \u0141odzi | work=Historia (History) | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-15 | author=BIP}}</ref> Location of the first trial, 2007 photo. \n| SubmitDate   = May 24, 1945, [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]] \n| date_decided = Last case: 1965, [[Cologne]]\n}}\n\nThe '''Che\u0142mno trials''' were a series of consecutive [[war-crime]] trials of the [[Che\u0142mno extermination camp]] personnel, held in [[Poland]] and in [[Germany]] following [[World War II]]. The cases were decided almost twenty years apart. The first judicial trial of the former ''SS'' men \u2013 members of the ''[[Schutzstaffel#SS units and branches|SS-Sonderkommando]] [[Che\u0142mno nad Nerem|Kulmhof]]'' \u2013 took place in 1945 at the District Court in [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a]], Poland. The subsequent four trials, held in [[Bonn]], Germany, began in 1962 and concluded three years later, in 1965 in [[Cologne]].\n\nA number of camp officials, gas-van operators and ''SS'' guards, were arraigned before the court on charges of war crimes and crimes against humanity committed at [[Che\u0142mno extermination camp|Che\u0142mno]] (a.k.a. ''Kulmhof'') in [[Occupation of Poland (1939\u201345)|occupied Poland]] in the period between December 1941 and January 1945. The evidence against the accused, including testimonies by surviving witnesses, former prisoners, and mechanics attending to repair needs of the ''SS'', was examined in Poland by Judge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz of the \u0141\u00f3d\u017a District Court (''S\u0105d Okr\u0119gowy w \u0141odzi'').{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=02ABWyc_Ks0C&pg=PA208&dq=%22testimonies+collected+by+Judge+Bednarz%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7N6UUZ2vMKLCyQGW6oH4DQ&ved=0CDcQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22testimonies%20collected%20by%20Judge%20Bednarz%22&f=false The Gas Vans (Appendix I), pp. 206&ndash;209]}} Three convicted defendants were sentenced to death,<ref name=\"UMD\" /> including the camp deputy commandant ''[[Oberscharf\u00fchrer]]'' Walter Piller (wrongly, Filer); the [[Nazi gas van|gas van]] operator ''[[Hauptscharf\u00fchrer]]'' Hermann Gielow (Gilow), as well as Bruno Israel from [[Ordnungspolizei|Order Police]] (his sentence was commuted to life). All three were members of the ''SS Special Detachment Kulmhof'' responsible for the extermination of Jews and non-Jews, during [[the Holocaust in Poland|the Holocaust in occupied Poland]].{{sfn | Montague| 2012 |loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=02ABWyc_Ks0C&pg=PA151&lpg=PA151&dq=Walter+Piller,+Hermann+Gielow,+SS-Sonderkommando+Kulmhof&source=bl&ots=3-lUGRISPS&sig=PY1Y-U8wOGDkYi6gYaVp0wLhwIk&hl=en&sa=X&ei=3OWUUfPSHY-byAHlyYGADQ&ved=0CCsQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=Walter%20Piller%2C%20Hermann%20Gielow%2C%20SS-Sonderkommando%20Kulmhof&f=false Extermination, pp. 151&ndash;152]}}\n\nIn the years 1962\u201365, a dozen ''SS''-men from Kulmhof were arraigned before the German court (''Landgericht'') in [[Bonn]], RFN. They were charged with the murder of 180,000 Jews in the camp.<ref name=\"JTA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.jta.org/1963/01/22/archive/jewish-survivors-of-chelmno-camp-testify-at-trial-of-guards |title=Jewish Survivors of Chelmno Camp Testify at Trial of Guards |publisher=Jewish Telegraphic Agency |work=JTA Archive |date=January 22, 1963 |accessdate=2013-05-17 |author=JTA |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140220122211/http://www.jta.org/1963/01/22/archive/jewish-survivors-of-chelmno-camp-testify-at-trial-of-guards |archivedate=2014-02-20 }}</ref> The jury deliberations continued for three years, with sentences ranging from 13 years' imprisonment to 13 months and 2 weeks. Half of the defendants were cleared of all charges and released by Germany.<ref name=\"poznan.jewish.org\" /><ref name=\"Lichtenstein\">{{cite web | url=http://www.fluchschrift.net/verbrech/november/011141.htm | title=01.11.1941. Errichtung des ersten Vernichtungslagers in Chelmno | publisher=Fluchschrift - Deutsche Verbrechen | work=Heiner Lichtenstein, Daten aus der Zeitgeschichte, in: Trib\u00fcne Nr. 179/2006 | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-17 | author=Fluchschrift}}</ref>\n{{multiple image\n| direction=vertical\n| header=The case of the Che\u0142mno death camp\n| header_background=#AFCFDE\n| width=270\n| image1=Che\u0142mno (Kulmhof) 1942 (Ko\u0142o).jpg\n| caption1=Deportation to Che\u0142mno. In this photo, loading of victims sent from the [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto|ghetto in \u0141\u00f3d\u017a]]\n| image2=Children headed for deportation.JPG\n| caption2=[[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto|Ghetto]] children rounded up for deportation to Che\u0142mno\n| image3=Destroyed Magirus-Deutz furniture transport van Kolno Poland 1945.jpg\n| caption3=A model of Magirus-Deutz gas van used for suffocation at the [[Che\u0142mno extermination camp]]. This particular van has not been modified, nevertheless it gives a good idea about the process\n| image4=PikiWiki Israel 7036 Chelmno extermination camp burial pits.jpg\n| caption4=Archeological excavations at the forest ''Waldlager'' camp where the corpses were cremated on rails, ashes cooled and shovelled into sacks to be trucked to the nearby river at night\n}}\n\n==1945 Che\u0142mno Trial in Poland==\nAfter liberation by the Soviet Army, the new government of Poland began its official investigation into the Che\u0142mno war crimes on May 24, 1945.<ref name=\"Montague-177\">{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA177&lpg=PA177&dq=Wladyslaw+Bednarz+1945&source=bl&ots=XK4QuNgEtL&sig=CmzFgr_M78CfuKcW3FAbwPZe_f8&hl=en&sa=X&ei=NJ2SUby7O-rVigLy5oC4CQ&ved=0CEsQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q=Wladyslaw%20Bednarz%201945&f=false | title=Epilogue (Judge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz) | publisher=Univ of North Carolina Press | work=Chelmno and the Holocaust: The History of Hitler's First Death Camp | date=Mar 15, 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Patrick Montague | page=177 | isbn=0807869414}}</ref> Although most Germans fled, Piller and Gielow were soon captured by the Soviets and brought back.{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA184&dq=%22on+June+6,+1945,+the+Polish+government+began+its+own+investigation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EJCXUYXwOIiviQLD4YCYBA&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22on%20June%206%2C%201945%2C%20the%20Polish%20government%20began%20its%20own%20investigation%22&f=false Epilogue, pp. 184&ndash;193]}}\n\nNotably, the trial of [[List of major perpetrators of the Holocaust|Holocaust perpetrators]] from Che\u0142mno was unlike any other war-crimes trial, because the camp had been essentially eradicated by the [[SS]], along with most traces of the mass murder. Truckloads of ashes of its victims were dumped in the [[Warta]] river daily, the \"palace\" was blown up with rubble removed to foundations, [[Nazi gas van|mobile gas-chambers]] and loot were driven back to Berlin, written records were destroyed, including train departure records. There was nothing to see for the commissars, or draw interest.<ref name=\"ushmm.org-Chelmno\">{{cite web | url=http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/en/article.php?ModuleId=10005194 | title=Chelmno | publisher=Copyright \u00a9 United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, Washington, DC | work=Holocaust Encyclopedia | date=May 11, 2012 | accessdate=May 18, 2013 | author=USHMM | format=permission granted to be reused, in whole or in part, on Wikipedia; [[OTRS]] ticket no. 2007071910012533 confirmed | quote=''Text from USHMM has been released under the [[GFDL]].''}}</ref> Some of the key evidence was mistakenly discarded in the trash in 1945 (i.e. over 5,000 pairs of damaged shoes from a destroyed synagogue in [[Ko\u0142o, \u0141\u00f3d\u017a Voivodeship|Ko\u0142o]]), or hauled away as usable materials, including wooden fencing and cremation grids; few people were aware of its importance.<ref name=\"Montague-177\" /> By comparison, other former [[death camp]]s were overflowing with direct evidence of war-crimes, as in the case of the [[Majdanek Trials|Majdanek trial]] decided several months before.<ref name=\"Majdanek-1 YV\">{{cite web|url=http://www1.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/microsoft%20word%20-%206622.pdf |title=Majdanek |publisher=Yad Vashem |work=Majdanek concentration camp |year=2007 |accessdate=2013-04-14 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071127031515/http://www1.yadvashem.org/odot_pdf/microsoft%20word%20-%206622.pdf |archivedate=November 27, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nJudge Bednarz soon ordered excavation of the waste in a ''Schlosslager'' burn pit. About 24,200 spoons, 4,500 knives, and 2,500 forks were found, among pots, pans, eyeglasses and many other half-burned items in the debris.<ref name=\"Montague-177\" /> It was also known that most of the victims were Jews from the [[\u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto]], where chronicles of ghetto operations were found; in addition, non-Jewish Poles, Soviet prisoners, about 5,000 Gypsies, and whole transports of children had been deported to Che\u0142mno where they were murdered. The SS Master Sergeant Walter Piller testified about the final phase of the camp operation, including 1944 deportations from \u0141\u00f3d\u017a.<ref name=\"Jacob\">{{cite web | url=http://sunday-news.wider-des-vergessens.de/?tag=walter-piller | title=\"Walter Piller\". Ein SS-M\u00f6rder \u00fcber die Ermordung Tausender Juden | publisher=Sunday news. Das Online Magazin | work=Das ehemalige Vernichtungslager Che\u0142mno | date=28 December 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-17 | author=Rena Jacob | language=German | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140716214936/http://sunday-news.wider-des-vergessens.de/?tag=walter-piller | archive-date=16 July 2014 | url-status=dead }}</ref> To circumvent the Nazi destruction of records and evidence, Judge Bednarz used \u0141\u00f3d\u017a ghetto records and estimates to arrive at the number of victims. Based on ghetto statistics together with testimonies, he estimated some 350,000 victims. He did not account for the period of camp inactivity.{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA184&dq=%22on+June+6,+1945,+the+Polish+government+began+its+own+investigation%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=EJCXUYXwOIiviQLD4YCYBA&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22on%20June%206%2C%201945%2C%20the%20Polish%20government%20began%20its%20own%20investigation%22&f=false Epilogue, p. 184]}} The range of estimated victims presented at the 1962 trial in Bonn was 180,000 with 152,000 as the lowest acceptable number.<ref name=\"zchor.org\">{{cite web | url=http://www.zchor.org/CHELMSUM.HTM | title=Review: Death Camp: \"Chelmno upon Ner\", Summary | publisher=We Remember | work=Janusz Gulczy\u0144ski: \"Ob\u00f3z \u015bmierci w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem\" (1991) | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Ada Holtzman}}</ref>\n\nThe first Che\u0142mno trial in Poland established many critical details from the camp history, but also revealed the operation of mobile [[gas chamber]]s, which used exhaust fumes as the killing agent, diverted into sheet metal-lined vans. The names of SS officials and commanders at the camp were established, including the ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Herbert Lange]] and the ''SS-Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Hans Johann Bothmann|Hans Bothmann]] who had vanished.<ref name=\"zchor.org\" />{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA175&dq=%22Sonderkommando+fled%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=cX6fUYS5Osm3iwKr0YDQDQ&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%22Sonderkommando%20fled%22&f=false Epilogue, p. 175]}}\n\n===Survivor testimonies===\nJudge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz, assisted by the Deputy Recording Clerk, heard testimonies of key witnesses including [[Simon Srebnik|Szymon (Simon) Srebrnik]] (age fifteen), who survived being shot in the head during the Germans' last execution of Jews at the camp, and [[Mordecha\u00ef Podchlebnik|Micha\u0142 (Mordecha\u00ef) Podchlebnik]], who escaped in 1942 into the surrounding forest from the burial ''[[Sonderkommando]]''. Podchlebnik testified on June 9, 1945. He was at the camp for 10 days digging mass graves in January 1942 at the time of the Nazi ''[[Operation Reinhard|Aktion Reinhard]]''. The cremation process was implemented there a year later.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-podchlebnik\" />\n\n{{quote|I figured that about 1,000 people were gassed every day... which filled three to four metres of trench... I had been trying to persuade my inmates to escape... On the way to work, I noticed that one of the windows on the bus could be lowered. I told my companion Winer from Izbica... we were separated and I had to get into the truck... I cut the tarpaulin... and jumped out of the car. They started shooting at me but all bullets missed the target. Luckily the bus did not follow the truck... After two days, during which I did not eat anything... {{grey|[}}I{{grey|]}} headed in the direction of [[Grab\u00f3w, Kutno County|Grab\u00f3w]] town. On my way I stopped at some peasant\u2019s cottages (I do not know his name). He gave me some food and a hat, shaved me and showed the way. In Grab\u00f3w I met Winer...| ''From'' [[Mordecha\u00ef Podchlebnik|Micha\u0142 Podchlebnik]], ''Chelmno Survivor Testimony''.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-podchlebnik\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/survivor/podchlebnik.html | title=Michal Podchlebnik, Chelmno Survivor Testimony | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Chelmno Survivor Testimony | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Chris Webb, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>}}\n\nThe second survivor from the Jewish ''Sonderkommando'', [[Simon Srebnik|Szymon Srebrnik]], was from \u0141\u00f3d\u017a and 15 years old at the end of the war. He testified on June 29, 1945 in [[Ko\u0142o]]; he was not under oath, although informed of criminal liability for a false statement. Srebnik worked at the forest camp during the second extermination phase, when the bodies were cremated after being delivered in the gas-vans.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-srebrnik\" />\n\n{{quote|In March 1944... we were in the ''Sonderkommando'' camp... The stronger and better workers were sent to the woods... The ''Waldkommando'' consisted of about 40 Jews... We were all shackled... The furnaces were very primitive, they stood on a cement foundation... They were approximately three metres (10 feet) tall. The width was about the same. The fire grate was made of narrow-gauge railroad railings... The capacity of one furnace was more or less the same as one [[Nazi gas van|van]]... It took approximately one hour for the corpses to burn. Then a new pile of bodies were added... While the clothes were being sorted, high ranking SS-men came and chose something for themselves...| ''From'' [[Simon Srebnik|Szymon Srebrnik]], ''Chelmno Survivor Testimony''.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-srebrnik\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/survivor/srebrnik.html | title=Szymon Srebrnik, Chelmno Survivor Testimony | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Chelmno Survivor Testimony | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Chris Webb, H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>}}\n\n===The defendants===\nOn October 29/30, 1945 Judge W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz questioned German ''Oberwachtmeister'' Bruno Israel (born Bruno Koenig), employed at the final phase of the Che\u0142mno extermination. He was accused of committing crimes against the Polish nation under the PKWN Decree of August 31, 1944 pertaining to Nazi War Criminals (the so-called ''[[:pl:Sierpni\u00f3wka|Sierpni\u00f3wka]].'' This provided for the death penalty without direct appeal).<ref name=\"DU-1944\">{{cite web | url=http://static1.money.pl/d/akty_prawne/pdf/DU/1946/69/DU19460690377.pdf | title=Dekret Polskiego Komitetu Wyzwolenia Narodowego z dnia 31 sierpnia 1944 | publisher=Internetowy System Akt\u00f3w Prawnych | work=Dziennik Ustaw Nr 69. Poz. 377. Zalacznik. | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-19 | author=ISAP | format=PDF file, direct download 110 KB}}</ref> The defendant claimed to be not guilty.\n\nBruno Israel testified the following:  \n{{quote|In July or August 1944... I was assigned to the ''Sonderkommando Kulmhof''... I took part in the escorting of the transports. When Jews asked where they were being taken, I answered... they were going to work. The Jews generally believed it and behaved peacefully... They were given soap, unless they had their own. They were told they would get towels at the bath-house. Then all of them, both men and women were herded into a corral at the exit of which there was a ''[[Nazi gas van|Sonderwagen]]'' (the van)... The [dead] bodies were thrown into one of the [''Waldlager''] crematoriums. The furnaces were about 10 meters wide and about 5-6 meters long. They did not stick out above the ground level. They had no chimneys.| ''Oberwachtmeister'' Bruno Israel, ''Chelmno Defendant Testimony''.<ref name=\"holocaustresearch-3\">{{cite web | url=http://www.holocaustresearchproject.org/trials/chelmnowachmeister.html | title=Bruno Israel, Chelmno Wachtmeister - Testimony | publisher=Holocaust Education & Archive Research Team | work=Trials. Protocol of the Interrogation | year=2009 | accessdate=2013-05-14 | author=Victor Smart,  H.E.A.R.T}}</ref>}}\n\nAlthough Bruno Israel was convicted of war crimes and sentenced to death, the Polish President [[Boles\u0142aw Bierut]] granted him clemency in September 1946, commuting his sentence to life. Israel was released conditionally for five years in November 1958, and was never required to return to prison.<ref name=\"UMD\" />\n\nStatutory death sentences were given to other two defendants, who were found guilty. Both Walter Piller and Hermann Gielow applied for a presidential pardon, which they were not granted. After a few years spent on [[death row]], Walter Piller was executed on January 19, 1949. Herman Gielow was executed in the [[Pozna\u0144]] prison on June 6, 1951.<ref name=\"UMD\" /> The very Decree of August 31, 1944 used in their sentencing was amended in December 1946, making the laws ''not applicable'' from the outset, in connection with the [[World War II crimes in Poland#The Soviet occupation|Soviet World War II crimes in Poland]].<ref name=\"DU-1944\" />\n\n==Che\u0142mno Trials in Germany 1962\u201365==\nEleven indicted suspects from Che\u0142mno were arraigned at the Special Criminal Court in [[Bonn]], RFN (''Landgericht Bonn'') in 1962\u201365 on charges of complicity to the murder of 180,000 Jews.<ref name=\"UMD\">{{cite web | url=http://www.gminadabie.pl/asp/pl_start.asp?typ=14&sub=283&menu=209&strona=1 | title=SS-Sonderkommando Kulmhof | publisher=Urz\u0105d Miejski w D\u0105biu (homepage) | work=Oddzia\u0142 Specjalny Kulmhof | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-16 | author=UMD}}</ref> A total of four trials were held. Later observers referred to at least one of them as a ''judicial farce''.<ref name=\"Lichtenstein\" /> Genocide was not in the criminal code of Nazi Germany and the court ruled that it could not be applied retroactively. Depositions were not sufficient to secure convictions. There was little physical evidence remaining at the crime scene. No victims' bodies to examine: their ashes had been carried downriver and out to sea.<ref name=\"JTA\" /><ref name=\"preventgenocide\">{{cite web | url=http://www.preventgenocide.org/punish/domestic/ | title=Paragraph \u00a7220a (genocide) of Germany's Strafgesetzbuch | publisher=Prevent Genocide International | work=Genocide and international crimes in domestic courts. Chapter: Germany | year=2013 | accessdate=2013-05-20 | author=PGI}}</ref>\n\nThe most severe penalties of 15 years were given to Gustav Laabs, ''SS Hauptscharf\u00fchrer'', a gas van operator, and Alois H\u00e4fele, ''SS Untersturmf\u00fchrer,'' a camp ''Hauskommando'' leader. The latter's sentence was reduced by two years on appeal because he reportedly gave cigarettes to some of the walking dead. Half of the defendants were cleared of all charges and released.<ref name=\"UMD\" /><ref name=\"poznan.jewish.org\">{{cite web | url=http://poznan.jewish.org.pl/index.php/zaglada/Osrodek-Zaglady-w-Chelmnie-nad-Nerem-Kulmhof.html | title=O\u015brodek Zag\u0142ady w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem (Kulmhof) | publisher=Poznanska Filia Zwiazku Gmin Wyznaniowych Zydowskich w RP | work=Holokaust | year=2008 | accessdate=2013-05-15 | author=Wojciech Meixner}}</ref> ''Oberscharf\u00fchrer'' Gustaw Fiedler, from ''Polizeiwachtkommando,'' was tried in 1965 in [[Cologne]] and sentenced to 13\u00bd months imprisonment.\n\n::{| width=\"98%\" border=\"1\" cellpadding=\"2\" cellspacing=\"0\" style=\"font-size: 90%; border: gray solid 1px; border-collapse: collapse; text-align: middle;\"\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|#\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Defendant <ref name=\"UMD\" />\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Born <ref name=\"AHF\" />\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Rank <ref name=\"AHF\">{{cite web | url=http://forum.axishistory.com/viewtopic.php?f=38&t=3031 | title=Chelmno Personnel | publisher=Axis History Forum | work=The Phil Nix SS & Polizei section | accessdate=2013-05-16}}</ref>\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Function\n! style=\"text-align:center;background:#B0C4DE\"|Sentence <ref name=\"UMD\" />\n|-\n|1||Gustaw Laabs||20 December 1902||''SS Hauptscharf\u00fchrer''||Gas-van operator||{{space|3}} 15 years imprisonment \n|-\n|2||Walter Burmeister||2 May 1906||''SS Unterscharf\u00fchrer''||Bothmann adjutant||{{space|3}} 13 years imprisonment\n|-\n|3||Alois H\u00e4fele||5 July 1893||''SS Untersturmf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp ''Hauskommando'' leader||{{space|3}} 15 years imprisonment \n|-\n|4||Kurt M\u00f6bius||3 May 1895||''SS Scharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} 8 years imprisonment \n|-\n|5||Karl Heinl||11 April 1912||''SS Unterscharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} 7 years imprisonment \n|-\n|6||Walter (Ernst) Burmeister <ref name=\"Klee\">{{cite book | title=The Good Old Days | publisher=The Free Press, NY |author1=Ernst Klee |author2=W. Dressen |author3=V. Riess | year=1988 | pages=219\u2013220}}</ref>||(''ntbcw'')||''Gaswagenfahrer''||Gas-van operator||{{space|3}} 3 \u00bd years imprisonment \n|-\n|7||Heinrich Bock||16 June 1912||''SS Scharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|8||Anton Mehring||25 March 1920||''Unterscharf\u00fchrer''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|9||Aleksander Steinke||16 March 1912||''{{nobreak|Polizei-Oberwachmeister}}''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|10||Friedrich Maderholz||7 November 1919||''Hauptscharf\u00fchrer''||SS Camp guard||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|11||Wilhelm Heukelbach||28 February 1911||''SS Oberscharf\u00fchrer''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|12||Wilhelm Schulte||23 June 1912||''Hauptscharf\u00fchrer''||SS personnel||{{space|3}} acquitted and released \n|-\n|13||Gustaw Fiedler||(''1965 trial'')||''Oberscharf\u00fchrer''||''Polizeiwachtkommando''||{{space|3}} 13 months 2 weeks imprisonment\n|-\n|}\n\nThe first camp commandant, ''SS Sturmbannf\u00fchrer'' [[Herbert Lange]], was killed in action on April 20, 1945 near Berlin. The second head of Che\u0142mno, ''Hauptsturmf\u00fchrer'' [[Hans Bothmann]] who made substantial improvements to the killing method in the final phase of the camp operation, committed suicide in British custody in April 1946.<ref name=\"zchor.org\" /><ref>{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Caa4rl8SHHwC&pg=PA338&lpg=PA338&dq=Hans+Bothmann+committed+suicide&source=bl&ots=R-ZDL2a8ij&sig=O01N_FuICGwD1eRPSdEkg5tw_0w&hl=en&sa=X&ei=mXiaUamrK6jziwKc0IGQCg&ved=0CFoQ6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=Hans%20Bothmann%20committed%20suicide&f=false | title=Two Souls in my Breast | publisher=Oxford University Press | work=Model Nazi: Arthur Greiser and the Occupation of Western Poland | date=Mar 22, 2012 | accessdate=2013-05-20 | author=Catherine Epstein | page=338 | isbn=0199646538}}</ref>\n\n==Poland 2001==\n\nThe last person charged in connection with the crimes at Che\u0142mno was a pole, Henryk Mania. He was one of eight polish prisoners who worked with the camp ''Sonderkommando''. Mania had been originally imprisoned after being accused of attempting to poison a german.<ref>[https://www.welt.de/welt_print/politik/article5364656/Eine-polnische-Parallele-zu-Demjanjuk.html Die Welt]</ref>. These eight prisoners has previously worked at a sonderkommando at [[Fort VII]] prison where they would dispose of dead prisoners. The men were then transferred to Che\u0142mno after being selected by Herbert Lange<ref name=\"seminare.pl\">{{cite web | url=http://www.seminare.pl/21/kolasa-spr1.doc | title=Mi\u0119dzynarodowa Konferencja Naukowa \"Fenomen Getta \u0141\u00f3dzkiego 1940\u20131944\" (\u0141\u00f3d\u017a 11\u201312 pa\u017adziernika 2004 r.) | publisher=Archiwum Pa\u0144stwowe w \u0141odzi (\u0141\u00f3d\u017a State Archives) | work=\u0141\u00f3d\u017a University, International \u0141\u00f3d\u017a Ghetto Conference 2004 | year=2004 | accessdate=2013-05-23 | author1=Izabela Matysiak-Aleksandrowicz | author2=Krzysztof Kolasa | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20060621161038/http://seminare.pl/21/kolasa-spr1.doc | archive-date=2006-06-21 | url-status=dead }}</ref> Fifty-six years after the end of World War II, he was convicted as an accessory to murder.{{sfn | Montague | 2012 | loc=[https://books.google.com/books?id=WvBRA0iGUjgC&pg=PA193&dq=%2256+years+after+the+end+of+the+Second+World+War%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=VJiXUc_BJeqSiQKvgYGgBg&ved=0CDEQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=%2256%20years%20after%20the%20end%20of%20the%20Second%20World%20War%22&f=false Epilogue, p. 193]}}.<ref>[https://trialinternational.org/latest-post/henryk-mania/ Trial International]</ref> \nHis investigation, begun in 1956, was renewed in 1991 by the [[Institute of National Remembrance]]. He was tried in a 2001 court case in [[Pozna\u0144]]. The [[Revolutions of 1989|collapse of the several communist/socialist governments]] and release of new records made it possible. Mania was found guilty of helping to load prisoners into gas-vans and collecting their watches and jewellery, which he also stole for himself. He was sentenced to 8 years' imprisonment, with consideration given to his advanced age.<ref name=\"\u015alusarek\">{{cite web | url=http://www.muzeum-kolo.pl/pl/images/stories/wydawnictwa-online/z-dziejow-zydow-kolskich.pdf | title=Zag\u0142ada kolskich \u017byd\u00f3w | publisher=Urz\u0105d Miejski w Kole | work=Z dziej\u00f3w \u017byd\u00f3w kolskich \u2013 w 70. rocznic\u0119 Zag\u0142ady. Sesja popularnonaukowa. Ko\u0142o 2012 | year=2012 | accessdate=2013-05-17 | author=Marta Szczesiak-\u015alusarek | page=65 | isbn=978-83-62485-66-6 | format=PDF file, direct download 855 KB | language=Polish}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Auschwitz Trial]] held in [[Krak\u00f3w]], Poland in 1947 against 40 SS-staff of the [[Auschwitz concentration camp]] death factory\n* [[Belsen Trial]]\n* [[Belzec Trial]] before the 1st [[Munich]] District Court in the mid-1960s of the eight SS-men of the [[Belzec extermination camp]] command\n* [[Dachau Trials]], held within the walls of the former [[Dachau concentration camp]], 1945\u20131948\n* [[Majdanek Trials]], the longest Nazi war crimes trial in history, spanning over 30 years\n* [[Mauthausen-Gusen camp trials]]\n* [[Ravensbr\u00fcck Trial]]\n* [[Sobibor Trial]], held in [[Hagen]], Germany in 1965, concerning the [[Sobibor extermination camp]] officials\n* [[Treblinka trials]] in D\u00fcsseldorf, Germany\n\n==Notes==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==References==\n*{{Citation | last=Montague | first=Patrick | year=2012 | title=Che\u0142mno and the Holocaust: The History of Hitler's First Death Camp | publisher=[[University of North Carolina Press]] | publication-place=Chapel Hill | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=02ABWyc_Ks0C&dq=Walter+Piller,+Hermann+Gielow,+SS-Sonderkommando+Kulmhof&source=gbs_navlinks_s | accessdate=May 24, 2013 | isbn=0807835277 | format=Google Books | quote=''Search inside.''}}\n*{{cite web | url=https://books.google.com/books?id=asCq3ZD0ObQC&lpg=PA428&dq=%22the%20examining%20judge%20of%20the%20district%20court%20in%20%C5%81%C3%B3d%C5%BA%2C%20W%C5%82adys%C5%82aw%20Bednarz%22&pg=PA184#v=onepage&q=Bednarz&f=false | title=Children in the Concentration Camp Universe | publisher=Rowman Altamira | work=Children during the Holocaust | date=May 31, 2011 | accessdate=2013-05-15 | author=Patricia Heberer | pages=184, 428 | isbn=0759119864}}\n*W\u0142adys\u0142aw Bednarz, ''Ob\u00f3z strace\u0144 w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem'' with Foreword by Wac\u0142aw Barcikowski, [[Pa\u0144stwowy Instytut Wydawniczy]] PIW, Warsaw&nbsp;1946&nbsp;{{in lang|pl}}\n*Janusz Gulczy\u0144ski, ''Ob\u00f3z \u015bmierci w Che\u0142mnie nad Nerem'', Wojew\u00f3dzki O\u015brodek Kultury: Muzeum Okr\u0119gowe, [[Konin]] 1991 {{in lang|pl}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Chelmno extermination camp}}\n[[Category:Che\u0142mno extermination camp| ]]\n[[Category:Holocaust trials]]\n[[Category:Trials in Poland]]\n", "name_user": "Kingbird1", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200ePoland 2001:Clean up/copyedit", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Che%C5%82mno_trials"}
{"title_page": "Maria Mandl", "text_new": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Maria Mandel\n| image         = Maria Mandel.jpg\n| image_size    = 220px\n| caption       = Mandl after her arrest by US troops, 1945\n| alias         = Maria Mandel<br />The Beast\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1912|1|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1948|1|24|1912|1|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[People's Republic of Poland]] (present-day [[Krak\u00f3w, Poland]])\n| death_cause   = [[capital punishment]] (hanging) \n| employer      = [[Aufseherin]], [[Lichtenburg (concentration camp)|Lichtenburg]], [[Oberaufseherin]], [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]], [[Lagerf\u00fchrerin]], [[Auschwitz II Birkenau]], women's camp at Birkenau, [[Dachau concentration camp]].\n| occupation    = [[Prison Guard]]\n| home_town     = [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]], Austria  \n| nickname      = The Beast\n| party         = [[Nazi Party|NSDAP]]}}\n\n'''Maria Mandl''' (also spelled '''Mandel'''; 10 January 1912 \u2013 24 January 1948) was an [[Austrian people|Austrian]]follow me on tiktok @.irisx ''[[Schutzstaffel|SS]]-[[Female_guards_in_Nazi_concentration_camps#Supervision_levels_and_ranks|Helferin]]'' known for her role in the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] as a top-ranking official at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]] [[extermination camp]] where she is believed to have been directly complicit in the deaths of over 500,000 female prisoners.<ref>[http://s3.photobucket.com/user/Rodoh_Hans/media/266_a.jpg.html Profile], s3.photobucket.com; accessed 16 November 2014.</ref> She was executed for war crimes.\n\n==Life==\nMandl was born in [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]], [[Upper Austria]], then part of [[Austria-Hungary]], the daughter of a shoemaker.\n\n===Camp work===\nAfter the ''[[Anschluss]]'' by [[Nazi Germany]], Mandl moved to [[Munich]], and on 15 October 1938 joined the camp staff as an ''[[Female guards in Nazi concentration camps|Aufseherin]]'' at [[Lichtenburg (concentration camp)|Lichtenburg]], an early [[Nazi concentration camp]] in the [[Province of Saxony]] where she worked with fifty other SS women. On 15 May 1939, along with other guards and prisoners, Mandl was sent to the newly opened [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]] near [[Berlin]]. She soon impressed her superiors and, after she had joined the [[Nazi Party]] on 1 April 1941, was elevated to the rank of a ''SS-Oberaufseherin'' in April 1942. She oversaw daily roll calls, assignments for ''Aufseherinnen'' and punishments such as beatings and [[flogging]]s.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nOn 7 October 1942, Mandl was assigned to the [[Auschwitz concentration camp#Auschwitz II-Birkenau|Auschwitz II-Birkenau]] camp  where she succeeded [[Johanna Langefeld]] as ''SS-Lagerf\u00fchrerin'' of the women camp under ''SS-Kommandant'' [[Rudolf H\u00f6\u00df]]. As a woman she could never outrank a man,{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} but her control over both female prisoners and her female subordinates was absolute. The only man Mandl reported to was the commandant. She controlled all the female Auschwitz camps and female subcamps including at [[Zabrze|Hindenburg]], [[Sv\u011btl\u00e1 Hora|Lichtewerden]] and [[Rajsko, O\u015bwi\u0119cim County|Raisko]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nMandl promoted [[Irma Grese]] to head of the Hungarian women's camp at [[Auschwitz II|Birkenau]]. According to some accounts, Mandl often stood at the gate into Birkenau waiting for an inmate to turn and look at her: any who did were taken out of the lines and never heard from again. At Auschwitz, Mandl was known as '''''The Beast''''', and for the next two years she participated in selections for death and other documented abuses. She signed inmate lists, sending an estimated half a million women and children to their deaths in the gas chambers at Auschwitz I and II.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\nMandl created the [[Women's Orchestra of Auschwitz]] to accompany roll calls, executions, selections and transports. An Auschwitz prisoner, Lucia Adelsberger, later described it in her book, ''Auschwitz: Ein Tatsachenbericht'':<blockquote>\"The women who came back from work exhausted had to march in time to the music. Music was ordered for all occasions, for the addresses of the Camp Commanders, for the transports and whenever anybody was hanged.\"<ref name=\"biodata\"/></blockquote>\n\nFor her services, Mandl was awarded the [[War Merit Cross]] 2nd class. In November 1944, she was assigned to the [[M\u00fchldorf]] subcamp of [[Dachau concentration camp]] and [[Elisabeth Volkenrath]] became head of Auschwitz, which were liberated in late January 1945. In May 1945, Mandl fled from M\u00fchldorf into the mountains of southern [[Bavaria]] to her birthplace, [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]].\n[[File:Maria Mandl 1947.tiff|thumb|right|Defendant Mandl at Krak\u00f3w, 1947]]\n\n==Arrest and execution==\nThe [[United States Army]] arrested Mandl on 10 August 1945. Interrogations reportedly revealed her to be highly intelligent and dedicated to her work in the camps. For some time she was held at Dachau Prison, and was filmed by the US Army in May 1945 sharing a cell with Elizabeth Ruppert.<ref>{{cite web |title=SS BUNKER, DACHAU SS COMPOUND, PRISON FOR MALMEDY MASSACRE DEFENDANTS, DACHAU, GERMANY ; MUNICH. [No.] 193, LANDSBERG (DACHAU) HANGINGS, LANDSBERG, GERMANY |url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/19807 |website=catalog.archives.gov |publisher=Department of Defense. Department of the Army (US) |accessdate=15 September 2019 |ref=Approx. minutes 2:50 - 3:05 |date=14 May 1946}}</ref> Mandl was handed over to the [[Polish People\u2019s Republic]] in November 1946, and in November 1947 she was tried in a [[Krak\u00f3w]] courtroom in the [[Auschwitz Trial]] and sentenced to [[Capital punishment|death by hanging]].<ref name=\"biodata\">[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/mmandel.html Biography], [[Jewish Virtual Library]]; accessed 15 November 2014.</ref>\n\nStanis\u0142awa Rachwa\u0142owa (a Polish survivor of Auschwitz who was an inmate under Mandl's administration and, after the war, was arrested by Poland's post-war communist authorities as an \"anti-communist activist\") was imprisoned in the cell next to Maria Mandl and [[Therese Brandl]]. Rachwa\u0142owa was proficient enough in German to interpret for the wardens. She stated that the last time she and the two German war criminals met \u2013 after they had been sentenced to death and shortly before their executions took place \u2013 both had asked her for forgiveness. Mandl was [[Hanging|hang]]ed on 24 January 1948, aged 36.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Female guards in Nazi concentration camps]]\n* [[Irma Grese]]\n* [[Ilse Koch]]\n\n==Sources==\n* Brown, D.P.: ''The Camp Women: The Female Auxiliaries Who Assisted the SS in Running the Nazi Concentration Camp System''; [[Schiffer Publishing]] 2002; {{ISBN|0-7643-1444-0}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandel, Maria}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sch\u00e4rding District]]\n[[Category:Auschwitz Trial executions]]\n[[Category:Austrian people executed abroad]]\n[[Category:Dachau concentration camp personnel]]\n[[Category:Executed Austrian women]]\n[[Category:Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp personnel]]\n[[Category:Auschwitz concentration camp personnel]]\n[[Category:Executed Austrian Nazis]]\n[[Category:Austrian people convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Executed mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Female guards in Nazi concentration camps]]\n[[Category:People convicted in the Auschwitz trial]]\n[[Category:People executed for crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Women sentenced to death]]\n", "text_old": "{{Refimprove|date=November 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name          = Maria Mandel\n| image         = Maria Mandel.jpg\n| image_size    = 220px\n| caption       = Mandl after her arrest by US troops, 1945\n| alias         = Maria Mandel<br />The Beast\n| birth_date    = {{birth date|1912|1|10|df=yes}}\n| birth_place   = [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]], [[Austria-Hungary]]\n| death_date    = {{death date and age|1948|1|24|1912|1|10|df=yes}}\n| death_place   = [[Krak\u00f3w]], [[People's Republic of Poland]] (present-day [[Krak\u00f3w, Poland]])\n| death_cause   = [[capital punishment]] (hanging) \n| employer      = [[Aufseherin]], [[Lichtenburg (concentration camp)|Lichtenburg]], [[Oberaufseherin]], [[Ravensbr\u00fcck]], [[Lagerf\u00fchrerin]], [[Auschwitz II Birkenau]], women's camp at Birkenau, [[Dachau concentration camp]].\n| occupation    = [[Prison Guard]]\n| home_town     = [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]], Austria  \n| nickname      = The Beast\n| party         = [[Nazi Party|NSDAP]]}}\n\n'''Maria Mandl''' (also spelled '''Mandel'''; 10 January 1912 \u2013 24 January 1948) was an [[Austrian people|Austrian]] ''[[Schutzstaffel|SS]]-[[Female_guards_in_Nazi_concentration_camps#Supervision_levels_and_ranks|Helferin]]'' known for her role in the [[The Holocaust|Holocaust]] as a top-ranking official at the [[Auschwitz concentration camp|Auschwitz-Birkenau]] [[extermination camp]] where she is believed to have been directly complicit in the deaths of over 500,000 female prisoners.<ref>[http://s3.photobucket.com/user/Rodoh_Hans/media/266_a.jpg.html Profile], s3.photobucket.com; accessed 16 November 2014.</ref> She was executed for war crimes.\n\n==Life==\nMandl was born in [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]], [[Upper Austria]], then part of [[Austria-Hungary]], the daughter of a shoemaker.\n\n===Camp work===\nAfter the ''[[Anschluss]]'' by [[Nazi Germany]], Mandl moved to [[Munich]], and on 15 October 1938 joined the camp staff as an ''[[Female guards in Nazi concentration camps|Aufseherin]]'' at [[Lichtenburg (concentration camp)|Lichtenburg]], an early [[Nazi concentration camp]] in the [[Province of Saxony]] where she worked with fifty other SS women. On 15 May 1939, along with other guards and prisoners, Mandl was sent to the newly opened [[Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp]] near [[Berlin]]. She soon impressed her superiors and, after she had joined the [[Nazi Party]] on 1 April 1941, was elevated to the rank of a ''SS-Oberaufseherin'' in April 1942. She oversaw daily roll calls, assignments for ''Aufseherinnen'' and punishments such as beatings and [[flogging]]s.{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nOn 7 October 1942, Mandl was assigned to the [[Auschwitz concentration camp#Auschwitz II-Birkenau|Auschwitz II-Birkenau]] camp  where she succeeded [[Johanna Langefeld]] as ''SS-Lagerf\u00fchrerin'' of the women camp under ''SS-Kommandant'' [[Rudolf H\u00f6\u00df]]. As a woman she could never outrank a man,{{citation needed|date=July 2015}} but her control over both female prisoners and her female subordinates was absolute. The only man Mandl reported to was the commandant. She controlled all the female Auschwitz camps and female subcamps including at [[Zabrze|Hindenburg]], [[Sv\u011btl\u00e1 Hora|Lichtewerden]] and [[Rajsko, O\u015bwi\u0119cim County|Raisko]].{{citation needed|date=November 2014}}\n\nMandl promoted [[Irma Grese]] to head of the Hungarian women's camp at [[Auschwitz II|Birkenau]]. According to some accounts, Mandl often stood at the gate into Birkenau waiting for an inmate to turn and look at her: any who did were taken out of the lines and never heard from again. At Auschwitz, Mandl was known as '''''The Beast''''', and for the next two years she participated in selections for death and other documented abuses. She signed inmate lists, sending an estimated half a million women and children to their deaths in the gas chambers at Auschwitz I and II.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\nMandl created the [[Women's Orchestra of Auschwitz]] to accompany roll calls, executions, selections and transports. An Auschwitz prisoner, Lucia Adelsberger, later described it in her book, ''Auschwitz: Ein Tatsachenbericht'':<blockquote>\"The women who came back from work exhausted had to march in time to the music. Music was ordered for all occasions, for the addresses of the Camp Commanders, for the transports and whenever anybody was hanged.\"<ref name=\"biodata\"/></blockquote>\n\nFor her services, Mandl was awarded the [[War Merit Cross]] 2nd class. In November 1944, she was assigned to the [[M\u00fchldorf]] subcamp of [[Dachau concentration camp]] and [[Elisabeth Volkenrath]] became head of Auschwitz, which were liberated in late January 1945. In May 1945, Mandl fled from M\u00fchldorf into the mountains of southern [[Bavaria]] to her birthplace, [[M\u00fcnzkirchen]].\n[[File:Maria Mandl 1947.tiff|thumb|right|Defendant Mandl at Krak\u00f3w, 1947]]\n\n==Arrest and execution==\nThe [[United States Army]] arrested Mandl on 10 August 1945. Interrogations reportedly revealed her to be highly intelligent and dedicated to her work in the camps. For some time she was held at Dachau Prison, and was filmed by the US Army in May 1945 sharing a cell with Elizabeth Ruppert.<ref>{{cite web |title=SS BUNKER, DACHAU SS COMPOUND, PRISON FOR MALMEDY MASSACRE DEFENDANTS, DACHAU, GERMANY ; MUNICH. [No.] 193, LANDSBERG (DACHAU) HANGINGS, LANDSBERG, GERMANY |url=https://catalog.archives.gov/id/19807 |website=catalog.archives.gov |publisher=Department of Defense. Department of the Army (US) |accessdate=15 September 2019 |ref=Approx. minutes 2:50 - 3:05 |date=14 May 1946}}</ref> Mandl was handed over to the [[Polish People\u2019s Republic]] in November 1946, and in November 1947 she was tried in a [[Krak\u00f3w]] courtroom in the [[Auschwitz Trial]] and sentenced to [[Capital punishment|death by hanging]].<ref name=\"biodata\">[https://www.jewishvirtuallibrary.org/jsource/biography/mmandel.html Biography], [[Jewish Virtual Library]]; accessed 15 November 2014.</ref>\n\nStanis\u0142awa Rachwa\u0142owa (a Polish survivor of Auschwitz who was an inmate under Mandl's administration and, after the war, was arrested by Poland's post-war communist authorities as an \"anti-communist activist\") was imprisoned in the cell next to Maria Mandl and [[Therese Brandl]]. Rachwa\u0142owa was proficient enough in German to interpret for the wardens. She stated that the last time she and the two German war criminals met \u2013 after they had been sentenced to death and shortly before their executions took place \u2013 both had asked her for forgiveness. Mandl was [[Hanging|hang]]ed on 24 January 1948, aged 36.<ref name=\"biodata\"/>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Female guards in Nazi concentration camps]]\n* [[Irma Grese]]\n* [[Ilse Koch]]\n\n==Sources==\n* Brown, D.P.: ''The Camp Women: The Female Auxiliaries Who Assisted the SS in Running the Nazi Concentration Camp System''; [[Schiffer Publishing]] 2002; {{ISBN|0-7643-1444-0}}.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Holocaust Poland}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mandel, Maria}}\n[[Category:1912 births]]\n[[Category:1948 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Sch\u00e4rding District]]\n[[Category:Auschwitz Trial executions]]\n[[Category:Austrian people executed abroad]]\n[[Category:Dachau concentration camp personnel]]\n[[Category:Executed Austrian women]]\n[[Category:Ravensbr\u00fcck concentration camp personnel]]\n[[Category:Auschwitz concentration camp personnel]]\n[[Category:Executed Austrian Nazis]]\n[[Category:Austrian people convicted of crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Executed mass murderers]]\n[[Category:Female guards in Nazi concentration camps]]\n[[Category:People convicted in the Auschwitz trial]]\n[[Category:People executed for crimes against humanity]]\n[[Category:Women sentenced to death]]\n", "name_user": "2001:982:fb8:1:a1ec:bd21:8822:8b3", "label": "vandal", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maria_Mandl"}
{"title_page": "Jeon So-mi", "text_new": "{{Short description|Canadian-Korean singer}}\n{{Distinguish|Jeon So-min}}\n{{Korean name|[[Jeon (Korean surname)|Jeon]]}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name            = Jeon So-mi\n| image           = 190613 Somi Birthday debut showcase (2).png\n| caption         = Jeon on June 13, 2019\n| native_name     = \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\n| birth_name      = Ennik Somi Douma\n| birth_date      = {{birth date and age|2001|03|09}}\n| birth_place     = [[Ontario]], Canada<ref>{{cite episode|title=Sister's Slam Dunk Season2 \uc5b8\ub2c8\ub4e4\uc758 \uc2ac\ub7a8\ub369\ud06c \uc2dc\uc98c2 \u2013 Ep.13|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=1X5EMPMjb3E|accessdate=May 12, 2017|series=Sister's Slam Dunk Season 2|series-link=Sister's Slam Dunk|network=[[KBS World]]|date=May 12, 2017|number=13|time=47:37}}</ref>\n| occupation      = {{hlist|Singer|dancer|songwriter}}\n| alias           = Somi\n| education       = [[Hanlim Multi Art School]]\n| awards          = [[#Awards and nominations|Full list]]\n| module          = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes\n| background      = solo_singer\n| genre           = [[K-pop]]\n| instrument      = Vocals\n| years_active    = 2015\u2013present\n| label           = {{hlist|[[JYP Entertainment|JYP]]|[[YMC Entertainment|YMC]]{{efn|name=labels|As a member of [[I.O.I]] only.}}|[[The Black Label]]}}\n| associated_acts = {{hlist|[[I.O.I]]|[[Unnies]]|[[JYP Nation]]}}\n| website         =\n| module          = {{Infobox Korean name|child=yes\n| title           = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul          = {{linktext|\uc804|\uc18c|\ubbf8}}\n| rr              = Jeon So-mi\n| mr              = Ch\u014fn Somi\n| hanja           =  {{linktext|\u5168|\u662d|\u5f4c}}\n}}}}}}\n\n'''Ennik Somi Douma''' (born March 9, 2001), known by her [[Korean name]] '''Jeon So-mi''' ({{Korean|\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8}}) or mononymously as '''Somi''', is a [[Korean Canadians|Korean Canadian]]/Dutch singer, dancer and songwriter based in South Korea, best known for finishing first in [[Mnet (TV channel)|Mnet]]'s survival reality program ''[[Produce 101 (South Korean TV series)|Produce 101]]'' and debuting in former South Korean girl group [[I.O.I]]. She made her debut as a soloist on June 13, 2019 with single \"[[Birthday (Somi song)|Birthday]]\".<ref name=\"Birthday release\">{{cite web|last=Herman|first=Tamar|title=K-Pop Star Somi Makes Every Day Her 'Birthday' in First Solo Single: Watch the Music Video|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/news/international/8515901/k-pop-somi-birthday-music-video|website=Billboard|accessdate=July 18, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\nJeon was born on March 9, 2001 in Ontario, Canada to a Korean mother, Jeon Sun-hee, and Dutch Canadian father, [[Matthew Douma]]. When she was one year old, her family moved to South Korea. Due to her mixed descent, Jeon was often bullied during her childhood days.<ref name=\"canadian\">{{cite web|last1=Williams|first1=Maxwell|title=Can Jeon Somi Become K-Pop's First International Biracial Superstar?|url=http://www.laweekly.com/music/can-jeon-somi-become-k-pops-first-international-biracial-superstar-7189819|website=LA Weekly|publisher=LA Weekly, LP|accessdate=January 8, 2017|date=2016-07-28}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeong|first1=Ji-won|title='\ud574\ud22c' \ub9e4\ud29c \"\ub538 \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \ud63c\ud608\uc544\ub77c \ub9c8\uc74c\uace0\uc0dd\u2026\uc18d\uc0c1\ud588\ub2e4\"|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000614687|publisher=Xports News|website=Naver|accessdate=January 19, 2017|language=ko|date=June 2, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeon|first1=Jong-seon|title='\uc2a4\ud0c0\uc1fc360' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uc131\uc219 \ubbf8\ubaa8 \uace0\ucda9 \ud1a0\ub85c\u00b7\u00b7\u00b7\"\uc544\ube60\ub791 \ub2e4\ub2c8\uba74 \ubd80\ubd80\ub85c \uc624\ud574\"|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=011&aid=0002893577|publisher=Sedaily|website=Naver|accessdate=February 10, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite episode|title=Sister's Slam Dunk Season2 \uc5b8\ub2c8\ub4e4\uc758 \uc2ac\ub7a8\ub369\ud06c \uc2dc\uc98c2 \u2013 Ep.2 [ENG/2017.02.24]|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=xvd1vPGe79E|accessdate=March 4, 2017|series=Sister's Slam Dunk Season 2|series-link=Sister's Slam Dunk|network=KBS World|date=February 24, 2017|number=2|time=31:11}}</ref> Jeon is a [[taekwondo]] [[Dan (rank)#Ranks in Korean|third-degree black belt]] holder but could not gain the fourth-degree like her father due to her age.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Yang|first1=Hyeong-jong|title='\uc8fc\uac04\uc544\uc774\ub3cc' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 \"\ud0dc\uad8c\ub3c4 3\ub2e8\"\u2026 \uacfc\uac70 '\ucd9c\ubc1c\ub4dc\ub9bc\ud300' \uc2dc\ubc94\ub2e8 \ucd9c\uc5f0|url= http://www.kyeongin.com/main/view.php?key=20161102010000835|website=Kyeongin Ilbo|publisher=Kyeongin Ilbo|accessdate=February 5, 2016|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nJeon graduated from Cheongdam Middle School on February 3, 2017 and [[Hanlim Multi Art School]], majoring in Practical Music and Vocal on February 7, 2020.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jang|first1=Young-hoon|title='\uc544\uc774\uc624\uc544\uc774' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\uc5d0 \ub300\ud574 \uc798 \ubab0\ub790\ub358 \uc0ac\uc2e4 6\uac00\uc9c0|url=http://www.insight.co.kr/newsRead.php?ArtNo=90542|publisher=Insight, Ltd|website=Insight|accessdate=January 19, 2017|language=ko|date=January 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=So-yeon|title=Jeon So-mi to enter high school|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201702031718386736085_2|website=Kpop Herald|publisher=Herald Corporation|accessdate=February 5, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Chae|first1=Hye-seon|title='\ub4dc\ub514\uc5b4 \uace0\ub4f1\ud559\uc0dd'\u2026\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 \uc9c0\ucf1c\ubcf4\ub294 \uc0b4\ubc8c\ud55c \uacbd\ud638\uc6d0\uc758 \uc815\uccb4|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=025&aid=0002690453|website=Naver|publisher=JoongAng Ilbo Co., Ltd|accessdate=March 2, 2017|language=ko|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201043737/http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=025&aid=0002690453|archive-date=2017-12-01|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=\uc878\uc5c5\uc7a5 \ub4e0 \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/001/0011384851|website=Naver|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2020|language=ko|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uc878\uc5c5\ud558\ub2c8 \uae30\ubd84\uc774 UP|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/421/0004449646|website=Naver|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2020|language=ko|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=|first1=|title=\"\ub354 \uc131\uc7a5\ud560\uac8c\uc694\"\u2026\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\u2192\uc788\uc9c0 \ub958\uc9c4\u00b7\ucc44\ub839, \uc624\ub298(7\uc77c) \uc878\uc5c5\u2192\ucd95\ud558 \ubb3c\uacb0ing [\uc885\ud569]|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/076/0003528665|website=Naver|publisher=|accessdate=February 8, 2020|language=ko|date=February 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n===Pre-debut===\nIn 2013, she appeared on the Children's Day Special of [[KBS2]]'s ''[[Let's Go! Dream Team Season 2]]'' as one of the representatives of Midong Elementary School's Taekwondo demonstration team, where she paired with [[Park Joon-hyung (comedian)|Park Joon-hyung]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Park|first1=Hyeon-taek|title=JYP-Mnet '\uc2dd\uc2a4\ud2f4' 6th \uba64\ubc84 \uc18c\ubbf8 \uacf5\uac1c '\ud0dc\uad8c\ub3c4 3\ub2e8'|url= http://news.jtbc.joins.com/article/article.aspx?news_id=NB10856400|website=JTBC News|publisher=Ilgan Sports|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko|date=2015-04-19}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Jo|first1=Jeong-nam|title='\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uacfc\uac70 '\ucd9c\ubc1c\ub4dc\ub9bc\ud300' \ucd9c\uc5f0 \ub2f9\uc2dc \ubcf4\ub2c8.. '\uc6b0\uc6d4 \ube44\uc8fc\uc5bc'|url=http://www.segye.com/content/html/2016/01/30/20160130000938.html|website=Segye|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko|date=2016-01-30}}</ref> In August 2014, she, her mother and her grandmother appeared on the 187th episode of ''[[Hello Counselor]]''. She also had a cameo role in the 2014 film ''[[Ode to My Father]]'' alongside her father and sister.<ref name=\"Cameo\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Min-ji|title=\uc18c\ubbf8, \uacfc\uac70 \ub2e4\uc591\ud55c \ud504\ub85c\uadf8\ub7a8\uc5d0 \uc5bc\uad74 \ub0b4\ube44\ucdb0 '\uc601\ud654 \uad6d\uc81c\uc2dc\uc7a5\uae4c\uc9c0'|url=http://www.nextdaily.co.kr/news/article.html?id=20150708800005|website=Next Daily|publisher=Next Daily|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko|date=2015-07-08}}</ref>\n\n===2014\u20132016: ''Sixteen'', ''Produce 101'' and I.O.I===\n{{Main articles|Produce 101 (season 1)|I.O.I}}\nIn 2014, Jeon joined [[JYP Entertainment]] (JYPE) after auditioning with [[2NE1]]'s \"[[Lonely (2NE1 song)|Lonely]]\", leading her to appear in [[Got7]]'s \"[[Identify (album)|Stop Stop It]]\" music video with other fellow female trainees.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kim|first1=Ji-young|title=JYP '\uac13\uc138\ube10' \ubba4\ube44\uc11c \ub2e8\uc5ed\uc73c\ub85c \ucd9c\uc5f0\ud55c \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8|url=http://www.insight.co.kr/newsRead.php?ArtNo=52309|publisher=Insight, Ltd|website=Insight|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Gi-eun|title=[TV\uc628\uc5d0\uc5b4] '\uc5b8\ub2c8\ub4e4\uc758 \uc2ac\ub7a8\ub369\ud06c2' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\u00b7\ud55c\ucc44\uc601\u00b7\uacf5\ubbfc\uc9c0, \ubbf8\uce5c\ub9e4\ub825 \ud130\uc84c\ub2e4 (\uccab\ubc29)|url=http://tvdaily.asiae.co.kr/read.php3?aid=14867399891210008019|publisher=TV Daily|website=TV Daily|accessdate=February 14, 2017|language=ko}}</ref>\nIn May 2015, Jeon participated in Mnet reality survival program ''[[Sixteen (TV series)|Sixteen]]'' where she was pitted against 15 other trainees from JYPE to secure a spot in the label's next girl group after [[Miss A]], later revealed to be named [[Twice (band)|Twice]]. However, she was eliminated in the final round, thus continuing as a trainee under the label.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Jae-heun|title=JYP criticized for casting process for new girl group|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/culture/2015/07/201_182419.html|website=Korea Times|publisher=The Korea Times|accessdate=February 5, 2017|date=2015-07-08}}</ref><ref name=sixteen>{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Seung-rok|title='\uc8fc\uac04\uc544' \ubc15\uc9c4\uc601 \"\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 '\uc2dd\uc2a4\ud2f4' \ud0c8\ub77d \uc774\uc720? \uac89\uc808\uc774 \uac19\uc558\ub2e4\"|url=http://entertain.naver.com/ranking/read?oid=117&aid=0002753500|website=Naver|publisher=My Daily|accessdate=February 7, 2017|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2016, Jeon represented JYPE on reality survival program ''[[Produce 101 (season 1)|Produce 101]]''. She finished in first place with 858,333 votes and debuted on May 4, with the project girl group [[I.O.I]], soon after debuting with the [[extended play|EP]] ''[[Chrysalis (EP)|Chrysalis]]'' under [[YMC Entertainment]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Seon|first1=Mi-kyung|title='\ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2a4101' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, 1\uc704 \uc9c0\ucf30\ub2e4\u2026\uc774\ubcc0\uc5c6\ub294 I.O.I \uba64\ubc84 11\uc778 \ud655\uc815[\uc885\ud569]|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20160402n00730|website=Nate|publisher=OSEN|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title='Produce 101' girls hold debuting media showcase|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/news/2016/05/05/0200000000AEN20160505003800315.html|publisher=Yonhap News Agency|website=Yonhap News|accessdate=January 19, 2017}}</ref> On August 29, Jeon collaborated with I.O.I band-mates [[Choi Yoo-jung (singer)|Choi Yoo-jung]] and [[Chungha (singer)|Chungha]] and [[Dia (band)|DIA]]'s [[Ki Hui-hyeon]] for the digital single, \"[[Flower, Wind and You]]\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Hwang|first1=Mi-hyeon|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5]\ubcf4\uc774\ube44, \uae30\ud76c\ud604\u00b7\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\u00b7\ucd5c\uc720\uc815\u00b7\uae40\uccad\ud558 \uace1 \ud504\ub85c\ub4c0\uc2f1|url=https://mnews.joins.com/article/20467510#home|website=Naver|publisher=Ilgan Sports|accessdate=July 25, 2019|language=ko|date=2016-08-18}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Choi|first1=Hyun-jung|title=\uae30\ud76c\ud604X\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8X\ucd5c\uc720\uc815X\uae40\uccad\ud558 '\uaf43, \ubc14\ub78c \uadf8\ub9ac\uace0 \ub108' \uc7ac\ud0b7 \uacf5\uac1c|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=382&aid=0000498600|website=Naver|publisher=Sports DongA|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> In October, Jeon was selected as the new host for [[SBS MTV]]'s ''[[The Show (South Korean TV series)|The Show]]'' along with [[UP10TION]]'s [[Kim Woo-seok (singer)|Wooshin]].<ref name=\"CJ E&M enewsWorld\">{{cite news|last1=Choi|first1=Shin-ae|url=http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/109083/|title=I.O.I's Jeon Somi and UP10TION's Woo Shin Selected As New 'The Show' MCs|publisher=Mwave|accessdate=January 17, 2017|date=October 7, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161009173444/http://mwave.interest.me/en/kpop-news/article/109083/iois-jeon-somi-and-up10tions-woo-shin-selected-as-new-the-show-mcs-all-kpop-news|archive-date=October 9, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n[[File:161219 \ubd88\ube5b\uac70\ub9ac \ucd9c\uc815\uc2dd \uc544\uc774\uc624\uc544\uc774 \uc9c1\ucc0d \uc5c5\ub85c\ub4dc (8).jpg|thumb|left|upright|Jeon So-mi in December 2016]]\n\n=== 2017\u20132018: Solo activities and departure from JYPE ===\nOn January 9, 2017, it was confirmed that Jeon signed a formal contract with JYPE for solo activities regarding Television appearances.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jeon|first1=Won|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=117&aid=0002861908|title=[MD\ud3ec\ucee4\uc2a4] \"\uc0c8\ub85c\uc6b4 \uc2dc\uc791\"\u2026\uc544\uc774\uc624\uc544\uc774, 1\uc6d4 \ud65c\ub3d9 \uc885\ub8cc \ud6c4 \uc5b4\ucc0c\ub418\ub098|website=Naver|publisher=My Daily|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=028&aid=0002351008|title=\uad7f\ubc14\uc774 '\uc544\uc774\uc624\uc544\uc774'|website=Naver|publisher=The Hankyoreh|accessdate=February 5, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> Soon after, she joined the cast of KBS2's ''[[Sister's Slam Dunk|Sister's Slam Dunk 2]]''.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kang|first1=Seo-jeong|url=http://news.nate.com/view/20170117n04556?mid=n1008|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] '\uc5b8\ub2c8\ub4e4\uc758 \uc2ac\ub7a8\ub369\ud06c2', \ud55c\ucc44\uc601\u00b7\uacf5\ubbfc\uc9c0\u00b7\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\u00b7\ud64d\uc9c4\uc601 \uc0c8 \uba64\ubc84\ud655\uc815|publisher=OSEN|website=Nate|accessdate=January 17, 2017|date=January 17, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kim|first1=Young-rok|title=\"\uc5b8\ub2c8\uc4f0 \ud30c\uc6cc\"\u2026'\ub9de\uc9c0?' \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 \uc62c\ud0ac, 15\uc77c '\ub300\uad50 \uacf5\uc57d' \uc2dc\ud589 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=076&aid=0003091378|publisher=Sports Chosun|website=Naver|accessdate=May 12, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> Jeon's activities with I.O.I soon came to an end following disbandment on January 29, 2017. On March 9, [[Eric Nam]] and Jeon released a collaborative digital single titled \"You, Who?\".<ref>{{cite web|last1=Herman|first1=Tamar|title=Eric Nam & Somi Share Springtime Duet 'You, Who?': Watch|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/7717997/eric-nam-somi-you-who-springtime-video|website=Billboard|publisher=Billboard|accessdate=March 10, 2017}}</ref> On May 12, Jeon debuted with Unnies, the project girl group created through ''Sister's Slam Dunk 2''. The group released the lead singles \"Right?\" and \"Lalala Song\".<ref>{{cite news|last1=Kim|first1=Young-rok|title=\"\uc5b8\ub2c8\uc4f0 \ud30c\uc6cc\"\u2026'\ub9de\uc9c0?' \uc74c\uc6d0\ucc28\ud2b8 \uc62c\ud0ac, 15\uc77c '\ub300\uad50 \uacf5\uc57d' \uc2dc\ud589 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201705130100099450006988&servicedate=20170512|website=Sports Chosun|accessdate=June 22, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, 2017 Jeon was cast in [[Korean Broadcasting System|KBS']] web entertainment program ''[[Idol Drama Operation Team]]''. She played a role as a high school student named Bo-ram. Final filming for the show was held on May 9.<ref name=IDOT/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Lim|first1=Jeong-yeo|title='Idol Drama Operation Team' now known as 'Don't Stray from the Flower Road'|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201705011645367047130_2|website=Kpop Herald|publisher=Herald Corporation|accessdate=May 12, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Jeong|first1=Jun-hwa|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \uc2ac\uae30X\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 '\uc544\ub4dc\uacf5', \uc624\ub298 \ub9c8\uc9c0\ub9c9 \ucd2c\uc601..29\uc77c \uccab\ubc29|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=109&aid=0003533022|publisher=OSEN|website=Naver|accessdate=May 12, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Kim|first1=Joo-ae|title='\uc544\ub4dc\uacf5' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 \"\ud559\uad50\uc5d0 \ub9e4\uc810 \uc5c6\uc5b4, \ube75\uc154\ud2c0 \ubcf8 \uc801 \uc5c6\ub2e4\"|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000738734|publisher=Xports News|website=Naver|accessdate=May 29, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> The seven cast members formed a project girl group called ''Girls Next Door'' and released a single as part of the show's soundtrack. The song titled \"Deep Blue Eyes\", co-written and co-composed by [[B1A4]]'s [[Jung Jin-young (singer)|Jinyoung]], was released on June 14 under [[Warner Music Group|Warner Music Korea]].<ref name=\"IDOT KBS\">{{cite news|last1=Jie|first1=Ye-eun|title=K-pop idols produce, act on own web entertainment series, 'Idol Drama Operation Team'|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170602000422|website=The Korea Herald|publisher=Herald Corporation|accessdate=June 17, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\uc544\uc774\ub3cc \ub4dc\ub77c\ub9c8 \uacf5\uc791\ub2e8 OST Part 2|url=http://music.naver.com/album/index.nhn?albumId=2065098|website=Naver Music|publisher=Naver Corporation|accessdate=June 17, 2017|language=ko}}</ref> In November 2017, Jeon featured on [[Jun. K]]'s digital single titled \"Nov to Feb\".<ref name=\"Nov to Feb\">{{cite web|url=https://itunes.apple.com/album/11%EC%9B%94%EB%B6%80%ED%84%B0-2%EC%9B%94%EA%B9%8C%EC%A7%80-nov-to-feb-feat-somi-single/1315547734|title=11\uc6d4\ubd80\ud130 2\uc6d4\uae4c\uc9c0 Nov to Feb (Feat. Somi) - Single|website=iTunes|publisher=Apple Inc.|accessdate=November 20, 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn August 20, 2018, JYP Entertainment released an official statement revealing that after mutual agreement, Jeon had terminated her contract, thus leaving the label.<ref>{{cite web|title=Jeon So-mi leaves JYP Entertainment|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201808201422112450433_2|publisher=Herald Corporation|website=Kpop Herald|accessdate=September 24, 2018}}</ref> In the following month, Jeon signed an exclusive contract with [[YG Entertainment]]'s subsidiary label [[The Black Label]], also home to South Korean [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]] singer [[Zion.T]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.xportsnews.com/?ac=article_view&entry_id=1022945|title=[\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5] \ub354\ube14\ub799\ub808\uc774\ube14 \uce21 \"\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8\uc640 \uc804\uc18d \uacc4\uc57d, \uc194\ub85c \uac00\uc218 \ub370\ubdd4 \uc900\ube44\"|website=Xports News|accessdate=September 24, 2018|date=2018-09-24}}</ref>\n\n=== 2019\u2013present: Solo debut ===\nOn February 25, 2019, The Black Label announced Jeon was preparing to make her debut as a solo artist with a lead single produced by [[Teddy Park|Teddy]].<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=\ub354\ube14\ub799\ub808\uc774\ube14 \"\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, 5\uc6d4 1\uc77c \uc194\ub85c \ub370\ubdd4 \ubaa9\ud45c\"(\uacf5\uc2dd)|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/stview.php?no=2019022513254536591|website=Star News|accessdate=February 25, 2019|date=2019-02-25}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, 6\uc6d4 13\uc77c \uc194\ub85c \ub370\ubdd4 \ud655\uc815\u2026\uc5ec\ub984 \uac00\uc694\ub300\uc804 \ud569\ub958 [\uacf5\uc2dd]|url=http://www.osen.co.kr/article/G1111145866|website=Osen|accessdate=May 20, 2019|date=2019-05-20}}</ref> Her debut single \"[[Birthday (Somi song)|Birthday]]\" was released on June 13, along with its accompanying music video.<ref name=\"Birthday release\"/> She made her first music show appearance as a solo artist on [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]'s ''[[Show! Music Core]]'' on June 15, performing both \"Birthday\" and its [[A-side and B-side|B-side]] \"Outta My Head\".<ref>{{cite web|last=|first=|title='\uc1fc \uc74c\uc545\uc911\uc2ec' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uc194\ub85c \ub370\ubdd4\u2026'\ubc8c\uc2a4\ub370\uc774' '\uc5b4\uc9c8\uc5b4\uc9c8' \ubb34\ub300 \uacf5\uac1c|url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201906151541208376&ext=na|website=My Daily|accessdate=July 1, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Jeon was confirmed as part of the cast for ''[[List of Law of the Jungle episodes#Chuuk|Law of the Jungle in Chuuk]]''.<ref name=Chuuk>{{Cite news|author=Jang Woo-young|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \u7236 \ub9e4\ud29c\uc640 '\uc815\uae00\uc758 \ubc95\uce59' \ub3d9\ubc18 \ucd9c\uc5f0\u2026\uc774\uc815\ud604\u00b7\ud55c\ud604\ubbfc\u00b7\uc720\uc7ac\ud658 \ub3d9\ud589 [\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5]|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1111245060|website=OSEN|date=October 21, 2019|accessdate=November 24, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> In 2020, [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]  announced that Somi will be joining ''Lose If You're Envious'' as an MC.<ref>{{Cite news|author=|title=\u2018\ubd80\ub7fd\uc9c0\u2019 \uce21 \u201c\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 MC \ud569\ub958\u201d \uc7a5\uc131\uaddc \uc7a5\ub3c4\uc5f0 \ud5c8\uc7ac\uc640 \ud638\ud761(\uacf5\uc2dd\uc785\uc7a5)|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/609/0000247452|website=Naver|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|author=|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8 MC\ud569\ub958, \uc62c\ud574 \ub098\uc774 20\uc0b4\u2026\"\ud48b\ud48b\ud55c \uc0ac\ub791\u00b7\uc5f0\uc560\uc5d0 \ub300\ud55c \uc0dd\uac01 \ubc1d\ud790 \uac83\"|url=http://m.etoday.co.kr/view.php?idxno=1857172|website=Etoday|date=February 14, 2020|accessdate=February 14, 2020|language=ko}}</ref> \n\nOn March 28, 2020, Somi's reality series, ''I Am Somi'', was released on [[The Black Label]]'s [[YouTube]] channel showing a daily v-log series of a 20 year old idol.<ref>{{cite web|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, 28\uc77c \uccab \uc720\ud29c\ube0c \ub2e8\ub3c5 \ub9ac\uc5bc\ub9ac\ud2f0 'I AM SOMI' \uacf5\uac1c|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/052/0001418497|website=Naver|accessdate=March 24, 2020|date=March 23, 2020|language=korean}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uc720\ud29c\ube0c \uccab \ub2e8\ub3c5 \ub9ac\uc5bc\ub9ac\ud2f0 \u2018\uc544\uc774 \uc5e0 \uc18c\ubbf8\u2019 28\uc77c \ub860\uce6d|url=https://n.news.naver.com/entertain/article/144/0000663123|website=Naver|accessdate=March 24, 2020|date=March 23, 2020|language=korean}}</ref>\n\n== Other ventures ==\n=== Endorsement ===\nIn July 2017, Jeon was selected for her first solo endorsement deal as a campaign model of [[The Coca-Cola Company|Coca-Cola Korea]] beverage brand, [[Fanta]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Lee|first1=Joo-hyun|url=http://news.naver.com/main/read.nhn?mode=LSD&mid=sec&sid1=105&oid=030&aid=0002622837|title=\ucf54\uce74\ucf5c\ub77c \ud658\ud0c0, \uc544\uc774\uc624\uc544\uc774 '\uc18c\ubbf8' \ubaa8\ub378 \uc120\uc815|website=Naver News|publisher=ET News|accessdate=July 19, 2017|language=ko}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=http://entertain.naver.com/read?oid=088&aid=0000497887|title='\uc194\uc9c1 \ubc1c\ub784' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uc62c \uc5ec\ub984 \ubb34\ub354\uc704 \uc9dc\ub9bf\ud558\uac8c \ub0a0\ub824\uc904 '\uc0c8\uc5bc\uad74'\ub85c \uae30\ub300|website=Naver|publisher=Maeil Sin Munsa|accessdate=July 19, 2017|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2018, Somi participated in the [[Reebok]] Classic SS18 campaign, \"Always Classic\".<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/8097323/somi-reebok-always-classic-campaign-exclusive-photos|title=Why Reebok Tapped K-Pop Star Somi for 'Always Classic' Campaign: 'She Encapsulates the Next Generation'|website=Billboard|accessdate=June 21, 2019|language=en}}</ref> On September 25, 2018 The Wetskills Foundation appointed Jeon as an International Wetskills Ambassador.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=23013302&cloc=|title=[\ub2e8\ub3c5] \uc18c\ubbf8, \ub124\ub35c\ub780\ub4dc NGO \ub2e8\uccb4 \ud64d\ubcf4\ub300\uc0ac\u2026\ub354\ube14\ub799 \uccab \ud589\ubcf4 |website=isplus|accessdate=June 22, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\nIn February 2019, Jeon was selected as a new model for ABC Mart's shoe brand Nuovo.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://sports.chosun.com/news/ntype.htm?id=201901300100220710017200&servicedate=20190130|title='2019\ub144\uc5d4 \uc88b\uc740 \uc77c\ub9cc' \uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \ub204\uc624\ubcf4 \uc544\uc2dc\uc544 \ubaa8\ub378\ub85c \ud65c\ub3d9\uc601\uc5ed \ud655\ub300|website=Sports Chosun|accessdate=April 30, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> In March 2019, Jeon and [[Ong Seong-wu]] were selected as advertising models for lifestyle sports brand Beanpole Sports.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.newsen.com/news_view.php?uid=201903050902484110|title='\ud504\ub4c0' \uc120\ud6c4\ubc30 \uc639\uc131\uc6b0X\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \ub208\ud638\uac15 \ubd80\ub974\ub294 \ud22c\uc0f7[\ud654\ubcf4]|website=Newsen|accessdate=March 8, 2019|language=ko}}</ref> On May 20, 2019 Jeon was chosen as the brand ambassador for cosmetics brand [[Shiseido]] Korea.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://tenasia.hankyung.com/archives/1724776|title=\uc804\uc18c\ubbf8, \uc194\ub85c \ub370\ubdd4\ubd80\ud130 \uc2dc\uc138\uc774\ub3c4 \ubaa8\ub378 \ubc1c\ud0c1 'So Me'|website=Ten Asia|accessdate=June 7, 2019|language=ko}}</ref>\n\n== Discography ==\n{{For|Jeon's work with [[I.O.I]]|I.O.I discography}}\n\n=== Singles ===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"3\" style=\"width:5em;\"| Title\n! scop